{"title_page": "Decision-making", "text_new": "{{short description|Cognitive process resulting in choosing a course of action}}\n{{about|decision making as analyzed in psychology|a broader discipline|Decision theory}}\n[[File:Wikipedia article-creation-2.svg|thumb|Sample [[flowchart]] representing a decision process to add a new article to Wikipedia.]]\n\nIn [[psychology]], '''decision-making''' (also spelled '''decision making''' and '''decisionmaking''') is regarded as the [[Cognition|cognitive process]] resulting in the selection of a belief or a course of action among several alternative possibilities. Decision-making is the process of identifying and choosing alternatives based on the [[value (ethics)|values]], [[preference]]s and beliefs of the decision-maker. Every decision-making process produces a final [[choice]], which may or may not prompt action.\n\nResearch about decision-making is also published under the label [[problem solving]], in particular in European [[psychological research]].<ref>{{cite book|title=Complex problem solving: the European perspective|date=1995|publisher=[[Lawrence Erlbaum Associates]]|isbn=978-0805813364|editor1-last=Frensch|editor1-first=Peter A.|location=Hillsdale, NJ|oclc=32131412|editor2-last=Funke|editor2-first=Joachim}}</ref>\n\n==Overview==\nDecision-making can be regarded as a problem-solving activity yielding a solution deemed to be optimal, or at least satisfactory. It is therefore a process which can be more or less [[Rationality|rational]] or [[Irrationality|irrational]] and can be based on [[explicit knowledge|explicit]] or [[tacit knowledge]] and beliefs. Tacit knowledge is often used to fill the gaps in complex decision making processes.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Brockmann |first1=Erich N. |last2=Anthony |first2=William P. |date=December 2016 |title=Tacit knowledge and strategic decision making |journal=[[Group & Organization Management]] |volume=27 |issue=4 |pages=436\u2013455 |doi=10.1177/1059601102238356}}</ref> Usually both of these types of knowledge, tacit and explicit, are used together in the decision-making process.\n\nHuman performance has been the subject of active research from several perspectives:\n* [[Psychology|Psychological]]: examining individual decisions in the context of a set of needs, preferences and values the individual has or seeks.\n* [[Cognition|Cognitive]]: the decision-making process regarded as a continuous process integrated in the interaction with the environment.\n* [[Normative]]: the analysis of individual decisions concerned with the logic of decision-making, or [[communicative rationality]], and the invariant choice it leads to.<ref name=\"Kahneman\">{{cite book |editor1-last=Kahneman |editor1-first=Daniel |editor1-link=Daniel Kahneman |editor2-last=Tversky |editor2-first=Amos |editor2-link=Amos Tversky |date=2000 |title=Choices, values, and frames |location=New York; Cambridge, UK |publisher=[[Russell Sage Foundation]]; [[Cambridge University Press]] |isbn=978-0521621724 |oclc=42934579 |page=[https://books.google.com/books?id=P5GsREMbUmAC&pg=PA211 211]}}</ref>\n\nA major part of decision-making involves the analysis of a finite set of alternatives described in terms of evaluative criteria. Then the task might be to rank these alternatives in terms of how attractive they are to the decision-maker(s) when all the criteria are considered simultaneously. Another task might be to find the best alternative or to determine the relative total priority of each alternative (for instance, if alternatives represent projects competing for funds) when all the criteria are considered simultaneously. Solving such problems is the focus of [[multiple-criteria decision analysis]] (MCDA). This area of decision-making, although very old, has attracted the interest of many researchers and practitioners and is still highly debated as there are many MCDA methods which may yield very different results when they are applied on exactly the same data.<ref name=MCDM>{{cite book |last=Triantaphyllou |first=Evangelos |title=Multi-criteria decision making methods: a comparative study |volume=44 |publisher=[[Kluwer Academic Publishers]] |series=Applied optimization |year=2000 |location=Dordrecht, Netherlands |page=320 |url=http://www.csc.lsu.edu/trianta/Books/DecisionMaking1/Book1.htm |isbn=978-0792366072 |doi=10.1007/978-1-4757-3157-6}}</ref> This leads to the formulation of a [[decision-making paradox]]. [[Logic]]al decision-making is an important part of all science-based professions, where specialists apply their [[knowledge]] in a given area to make informed decisions. For example, medical decision-making often involves a [[Medical diagnosis|diagnosis]] and the selection of appropriate treatment. But [[naturalistic decision-making]] research shows that in situations with higher time pressure, higher stakes, or increased ambiguities, experts may use [[Intuition (psychology)|intuitive]] decision-making rather than structured approaches. They may follow a [[recognition primed decision]] that fits their experience and arrive at a course of action without weighing alternatives.{{citation needed|date=January 2014}}\n\nThe decision-maker's environment can play a part in the decision-making process. For example, environmental complexity is a factor that influences cognitive function.<ref name=\"necsi.edu\">{{cite book |last1=Davidson |first1=Alice Ware |last2=Bar-Yam |first2=Yaneer |date=2006 |origyear=2000 |chapter=Environmental complexity: information for human\u2013environment well-being |editor1-last=Bar-Yam |editor1-first=Yaneer |editor2-last=Minai |editor2-first=Ali |title=Unifying themes in complex systems |location=Berlin; New York |publisher=Springer |pages=157\u2013168 |isbn=9783540358640 |doi=10.1007/978-3-540-35866-4_16 |chapterurl=http://necsi.edu/projects/yaneer/envcomplexity00.pdf|citeseerx=10.1.1.33.7118 }}</ref> A complex environment is an environment with a large number of different possible states which come and go over time.<ref name=\"its.caltech.edu\">{{cite book |last=Godfrey-Smith |first=Peter |authorlink=Peter Godfrey-Smith |date=2001 |chapter=Environmental complexity and the evolution of cognition |editor1-last=Sternberg |editor1-first=Robert J. |editor1-link=Robert Sternberg |editor2-last=Kaufman |editor2-first=James C. |editor2-link=James C. Kaufman |title=The evolution of intelligence |location=Mahwah, NJ |publisher=[[Lawrence Erlbaum Associates]] |pages=223\u2013250 |isbn=978-0805832679 |oclc=44775038 |chapterurl=http://www.its.caltech.edu/~theory/Godfrey-Smith.pdf}}</ref> Studies done at the [[University of Colorado]] have shown that more complex environments correlate with higher cognitive function, which means that a decision can be influenced by the location. One experiment measured complexity in a room by the number of small objects and appliances present; a simple room had less of those things. Cognitive function was greatly affected by the higher measure of environmental complexity making it easier to think about the situation and make a better decision.<ref name=\"necsi.edu\"/>\n\n== Problem solving vs. decision making ==\n{{More citations needed section|date=July 2015}}\n\nIt is important to differentiate between [[problem analysis]] and decision-making. Traditionally, it is argued that problem analysis must be done first, so that the information gathered in that process may be used towards decision-making.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Kepner |first1=Charles Higgins |last2=Tregoe |first2=Benjamin B. |authorlink2=Benjamin Tregoe |date=1997 |origyear=1965 |title=The new rational manager: an updated edition for a new world |edition=Updated |location=Princeton, NJ |publisher=Princeton Research Press |oclc=37666447 |ref=harv}}</ref>{{Page needed|date=July 2015}}\n\n; Characteristics of problem analysis:\n* Problems are merely deviations from performance standards\n* Problems must be precisely identified and described\n* Problems are caused by a change from a distinctive feature\n* Something can always be used to distinguish between what has and hasn't been affected by a cause\n* Causes of problems can be deduced from relevant changes found in analyzing the problem\n* Most likely cause of a problem is the one that exactly explains all the facts, while having the fewest (or weakest) assumptions ([[Occam's razor]]).\n\n; Characteristics of decision-making:\n* Objectives must first be established\n* Objectives must be classified and placed in order of importance\n* Alternative actions must be developed\n* The alternatives must be evaluated against all the objectives\n* The alternative that is able to achieve all the objectives is the tentative decision\n* The tentative decision is evaluated for more possible consequences\n* The decisive actions are taken, and additional actions are taken to prevent any adverse consequences from becoming problems and starting both systems (problem analysis and decision-making) all over again\n* There are steps that are generally followed that result in a decision model that can be used to determine an optimal production plan<ref>{{cite book |last=Monahan |first=George E. |date=2000 |title=Management decision making: spreadsheet modeling, analysis, and application |location=Cambridge, UK; New York |publisher=[[Cambridge University Press]] |isbn=978-0521781183 |oclc=42921287 |pages=[https://books.google.com/books?id=kOAKlA-PJTkC&pg=PA33 33\u201340]}}</ref>\n* In a situation featuring conflict, [[role-playing]] may be helpful for predicting decisions to be made by involved parties<ref>{{cite book |last=Armstrong |first=Jon Scott |date=2001 |chapter=Role playing: a method to forecast decisions |editor-last=Armstrong |editor-first=Jon Scott |title=Principles of forecasting: a handbook for researchers and practitioners |volume=30 |series=International series in operations research & management science |location=Boston, MA |publisher=[[Kluwer Academic Publishers]] |pages=15\u201330 |isbn=978-0792379300 |doi=10.1007/978-0-306-47630-3_2|citeseerx=10.1.1.464.5677 }}</ref>\n\n===Analysis paralysis===\n{{Main|Analysis paralysis}}\n\n[[Analysis paralysis]] is the state of over-analyzing (or over-thinking) a situation so that a decision or action is never taken, in effect paralyzing the outcome.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://en.oxforddictionaries.com/definition/us/analysis_paralysis|title=analysis paralysis {{!}} Definition of analysis paralysis in US English by Oxford Dictionaries|website=Oxford Dictionaries {{!}} English|access-date=2018-11-10}}</ref>\n\n===Information overload===\n{{Main|Information overload}}\n\nInformation overload is \"a gap between the volume of information and the tools we have to assimilate\" it.<ref>[[Paul Saffo]] quoted in: {{cite magazine |url=http://www.informationweek.com/551/51mtinf.htm |date=30 October 1995 |title=Managing information: infoglut |last=Foley |first=John |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20010222082946/http://www.informationweek.com/551/51mtinf.htm |archivedate=2001-02-22 |accessdate=2015-07-26 |magazine=[[InformationWeek]]}}</ref> Information used in decision making is to reduce or eliminate uncertainty.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Duncan|date=1972|title=Characteristics of organizational environments and perceived environment uncertainty|url=|journal=Administrative Science Quarterly|volume=17|issue=3|pages=313\u201327|doi=10.2307/2392145|jstor=2392145}}</ref> Excessive information affects problem processing and tasking, which affects decision-making.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Kutty |first1=Ambalika D. |last2=Kumar Shee |first2=Himanshu |last3=Pathak |first3=R. D. |date=November 2007 |title=Decision-making: too much info! |journal=Monash Business Review |volume=3 |issue=3 |pages=8\u20139 |doi=10.2104/mbr07056 |url=http://arrow.monash.edu.au/hdl/1959.1/787807 }}{{Dead link|date=July 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> Crystal C. Hall and colleagues described an \"illusion of knowledge\", which means that as individuals encounter too much knowledge it can interfere with their ability to make rational decisions.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Hall |first1=Crystal C. |last2=Ariss |first2=Lynn |last3=Todorov |first3=Alexander |date=July 2007 |title=The illusion of knowledge: when more information reduces accuracy and increases confidence |journal=Organizational Behavior and Human Decision Processes |volume=103 |issue=2 |pages=277\u2013290 |doi=10.1016/j.obhdp.2007.01.003 |url=http://courses.washington.edu/pbafhall/514/514%20Readings/Hall-OBHDP.pdf}}</ref>\n\n===Post-decision analysis===\n\nEvaluation and analysis of past decisions is complementary to decision-making. See also [[Mental accounting]] and [[Postmortem documentation]].\n\n== Neuroscience ==\n\nDecision-making is a region of intense study in the fields of [[systems neuroscience]], and [[cognitive neuroscience]]. Several brain structures, including the [[anterior cingulate cortex]] (ACC), [[orbitofrontal cortex]] and the overlapping [[ventromedial prefrontal cortex]] are believed to be involved in decision-making processes. A [[neuroimaging]] study<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Walton|first1=Mark E.|last2=Devlin|first2=Joseph T.|last3=Rushworth|first3=Matthew F. S.|date=November 2004|title=Interactions between decision making and performance monitoring within prefrontal cortex|journal=[[Nature Neuroscience]]|volume=7|issue=11|pages=1259\u20131265|doi=10.1038/nn1339|pmid=15494729}}</ref> found distinctive patterns of neural activation in these regions depending on whether decisions were made on the basis of perceived personal [[Volition (psychology)|volition]] or following directions from someone else. Patients with damage to the [[ventromedial prefrontal cortex]] have difficulty making advantageous decisions.<ref>{{cite book|title=Descartes' error: emotion, reason, and the human brain|last=Damasio|first=Antonio R.|date=1994|publisher=Putnam|isbn=978-0399138942|location=New York|oclc=30780083|authorlink=Antonio Damasio|url=https://archive.org/details/descarteserrorem00dama}}</ref>{{Page needed|date=July 2015}}\n\nA common laboratory paradigm for studying neural decision-making is the [[two-alternative forced choice]] task (2AFC), in which a subject has to choose between two alternatives within a certain time. A study of a [[two-alternative forced choice]] task involving [[rhesus monkey]]s found that neurons in the [[parietal cortex]] not only represent the formation of a decision<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Gold|first1=Joshua I.|last2=Shadlen|first2=Michael N.|date=2007|title=The neural basis of decision making|journal=Annual Review of Neuroscience|volume=30|pages=535\u2013574|doi=10.1146/annurev.neuro.29.051605.113038|pmid=17600525}}</ref> but also signal the degree of certainty (or \"confidence\") associated with the decision.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Kiani|first1=Roozbeh|last2=Shadlen|first2=Michael N.|date=May 2009|title=Representation of confidence associated with a decision by neurons in the parietal cortex|journal=Science|volume=324|issue=5928|pages=759\u2013764|doi=10.1126/science.1169405|pmc=2738936|pmid=19423820}}</ref> Another recent study found that lesions to the ACC in the [[macaque]] resulted in impaired decision-making in the long run of reinforcement guided tasks suggesting that the ACC may be involved in evaluating past reinforcement information and guiding future action.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Kennerley|first1=Steven W.|last2=Walton|first2=Mark E.|last3=Behrens|first3=Timothy E. J.|last4=Buckley|first4=Mark J.|last5=Rushworth|first5=Matthew F. S.|date=July 2006|title=Optimal decision making and the anterior cingulate cortex|journal=[[Nature Neuroscience]]|volume=9|issue=7|pages=940\u2013947|doi=10.1038/nn1724|pmid=16783368}}</ref> A 2012 study found that rats and humans can optimally accumulate incoming sensory evidence, to make statistically optimal decisions.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Brunton|first1=Bingni W.|last2=Botvinick|first2=Matthew M.|last3=Brody|first3=Carlos D.|date=April 2013|title=Rats and humans can optimally accumulate evidence for decision-making|url=http://www.princeton.edu/~matthewb/Publications/Science-2013-Brunton-95-8.pdf|url-status=dead|journal=Science|volume=340|issue=6128|pages=95\u201398|doi=10.1126/science.1233912|pmid=23559254|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160305005810/http://www.princeton.edu/~matthewb/Publications/Science-2013-Brunton-95-8.pdf|archive-date=2016-03-05}}</ref>\n\n=== Emotions ===\n{{Main|Emotions in decision-making}}\n[[Emotion]] appears able to aid the decision-making process. Decision-making often occurs in the face of [[uncertainty]] about whether one's choices will lead to benefit or harm (see also [[Risk]]). The [[somatic marker hypothesis]] is a [[Neurobiology|neurobiological]] theory of how decisions are made in the face of uncertain outcome.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Reimann|first1=Martin|last2=Bechara|first2=Antoine|date=October 2010|title=The somatic marker framework as a neurological theory of decision-making: review, conceptual comparisons, and future neuroeconomics research|journal=[[Journal of Economic Psychology]]|volume=31|issue=5|pages=767\u2013776|doi=10.1016/j.joep.2010.03.002}}</ref> This theory holds that such decisions are aided by emotions, in the form of bodily states, that are elicited during the deliberation of future consequences and that mark different options for behavior as being advantageous or disadvantageous. This process involves an interplay between neural systems that elicit emotional/bodily states and neural systems that map these emotional/bodily states.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Naqvi|first1=Nasir|last2=Shiv|first2=Baba|last3=Bechara|first3=Antoine|date=October 2006|title=The role of emotion in decision making: a cognitive neuroscience perspective|url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/228449030|journal=[[Current Directions in Psychological Science]]|volume=15|issue=5|pages=260\u2013264|citeseerx=10.1.1.137.4677|doi=10.1111/j.1467-8721.2006.00448.x}}</ref> A recent lesion mapping study of 152 patients with focal brain lesions conducted by [[Aron K. Barbey]] and colleagues provided evidence to help discover the neural mechanisms of [[emotional intelligence]].<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Barbey|first1=Aron K.|last2=Colom|first2=Roberto|last3=Grafman|first3=Jordan|date=March 2014|title=Distributed neural system for emotional intelligence revealed by lesion mapping|url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/233916334|journal=Social Cognitive and Affective Neuroscience|volume=9|issue=3|pages=265\u2013272|doi=10.1093/scan/nss124|pmc=3980800|pmid=23171618}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.illinois.edu/news/13/0122emotional_intelligence_AronBarbey.html|title=Researchers map emotional intelligence in the brain|last1=Yates|first1=Diana|website=University of Illinois News Bureau|publisher=[[University of Illinois]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://health.usnews.com/health-news/news/articles/2013/01/28/scientists-complete-1st-map-of-emotional-intelligence-in-the-brain|title=Scientists complete 1st map of 'emotional intelligence' in the brain|author=HealthDay|date=2013-01-28|agency=[[US News and World Report]]}}</ref>\n\n== Decision-making techniques ==\n\nDecision-making techniques can be separated into two broad categories: [[group decision-making]] techniques and individual decision-making techniques. Individual decision-making techniques can also often be applied by a group.\n\n===Group===\n* [[Consensus decision-making]] tries to avoid \"winners\" and \"losers\". Consensus requires that a majority approve a given course of action, but that the minority agree to go along with the course of action. In other words, if the minority opposes the course of action, consensus requires that the course of action be modified to remove objectionable features.\n* [[Voting|Voting-based methods]]:\n** [[Majority]] requires support from more than 50% of the members of the group. Thus, the bar for action is lower than with consensus.\n** [[Plurality voting system|Plurality]], where the largest block in a group decides, even if it falls short of a majority.\n** [[Quadratic voting]] allows participants to cast their ''preference'' and ''intensity of preference'' for each decision (as opposed to a simple ''for'' or ''against'' decision). It addresses issues of [[voting paradox]] and [[Majority rule|majority-rule]].\n** [[Range voting]] lets each member score one or more of the available options. The option with the highest average is chosen. This method has experimentally been shown to produce the lowest [[Bayesian regret]] among common voting methods, even when voters are strategic.{{citation needed|date=December 2011}}\n* [[Delphi method]] is a structured communication technique for groups, originally developed for collaborative forecasting but has also been used for [[Delphi method#Use in policy-making|policy making]].\n* [[Dotmocracy]] is a facilitation method that relies on the use of special forms called Dotmocracy Sheets to allow large groups to collectively brainstorm and recognize agreement on an unlimited number of ideas they have authored.\n* [[Participative decision-making]] occurs when an authority opens up the decision-making process to a group of people for a collaborative effort.\n* [[Decision engineering]] uses a visual map of the decision-making process based on [[system dynamics]] and can be automated through a decision modeling tool, integrating [[big data]], [[machine learning]], and expert knowledge as appropriate.\n\n===Individual===\n* [[Decisional balance sheet]]: listing the advantages and disadvantages (benefits and costs, pros and cons) of each option, as suggested by [[Plato]]'s ''[[Protagoras (dialogue)|Protagoras]]'' and by [[Benjamin Franklin]].<ref>{{cite book |last=Franklin |first=Benjamin |authorlink=Benjamin Franklin |date=1975 |origyear=1772 |chapter=To Joseph Priestley |editor-last=Willcox |editor-first=William Bradford |title=The papers of Benjamin Franklin: January 1 through December 31, 1772 |volume=19 |location=New Haven |publisher=[[Yale University Press]] |pages=299\u2013300 |isbn=978-0300018653 |oclc=310601 |chapterurl=http://franklinpapers.org/yale?vol=19&page=299a |ref=harv}}</ref>\n* [[Expected utility hypothesis|Expected-value optimization]]: choosing the alternative with the highest probability-weighted [[utility]], possibly with some consideration for [[risk aversion]]. This may involve considering the [[opportunity cost]] of different alternatives. See also [[Decision analysis]] and [[Decision theory]].\n* [[Satisficing]]: examining alternatives only until the first acceptable one is found. The opposite is [[Maximization (psychology)|maximizing]] or [[optimizing]], in which many or all alternatives are examined in order to find the best option.\n* [[Argument from authority|Acquiesce to a person in authority]] or an \"expert\"; \"[[Superior orders|just following orders]]\".\n* [[Anti-authoritarianism]]: taking the most opposite action compared to the advice of mistrusted authorities.\n* [[Flipism]] e.g. flipping a coin, cutting a deck of playing cards, and other random or coincidence methods{{spaced ndash}}or prayer, [[tarot]] cards, astrology, [[augurs]], [[revelation]], or other forms of [[divination]], superstition or [[pseudoscience]].\n* [[Automated decision support]]: setting up criteria for automated decisions.\n* [[Decision support system]]s: using [[decision-making software]] when faced with highly complex decisions or when considering many stakeholders, categories, or other factors that affect decisions.\n\n== Steps ==\nA variety of researchers have formulated similar prescriptive steps aimed at improving decision-making.\n\n===GOFER<!--This section is linked from [[Gofer (disambiguation)]] and [[GROW model]] ([[MOS:HEAD]])-->===\nIn the 1980s, psychologist Leon Mann and colleagues developed a decision-making process called GOFER, which they taught to adolescents, as summarized in the book ''Teaching Decision Making To Adolescents''.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Mann |first1=Leon |last2=Harmoni |first2=Ros |last3=Power |first3=Colin |date=1991 |chapter=The GOFER course in decision making |editor1-last=Baron |editor1-first=Jonathan |editor2-last=Brown |editor2-first=Rex V. |title=Teaching decision making to adolescents |location=Hillsdale, NJ |publisher=[[Lawrence Erlbaum Associates]] |pages=61\u201378 |isbn=978-0805804973 |oclc=22507012 |chapterurl=https://books.google.com/books?hl=en&lr=&id=voRVQEAZJYYC&pg=PA61}} See also: {{cite journal |last=Mann |first=Leon |date=July 1989 |title=Becoming a better decision maker |journal=Australian Psychologist |volume=24 |issue=2 |pages=141\u2013155 |doi=10.1080/00050068908259558}}</ref> The process was based on extensive earlier research conducted with psychologist [[Irving Janis]].<ref>{{cite book |last1=Janis |first1=Irving L. |authorlink1=Irving Janis |last2=Mann |first2=Leon |date=1977 |title=Decision making: a psychological analysis of conflict, choice, and commitment |location=New York |publisher=[[Free Press (publisher)|Free Press]] |isbn=978-0029161609 |oclc=2542340 |url=https://archive.org/details/decisionmakingps00janirich }}</ref> GOFER is an [[acronym]] for five decision-making steps:<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Mann |first1=Leon |last2=Harmoni |first2=Ros |last3=Power |first3=Colin |last4=Beswick |first4=Gery |last5=Ormond |first5=Cheryl |date=July 1988 |title=Effectiveness of the GOFER course in decision making for high school students |journal=Journal of Behavioral Decision Making |volume=1 |issue=3 |pages=159\u2013168 |doi=10.1002/bdm.3960010304}}</ref>\n\n# '''G'''oals clarification: Survey values and objectives.\n# '''O'''ptions generation: Consider a wide range of alternative actions.\n# '''F'''acts-finding: Search for information.\n# Consideration of '''E'''ffects: Weigh the positive and negative consequences of the options.\n# '''R'''eview and implementation: Plan how to review the options and implement them.\n\n===DECIDE===\nIn 2008, Kristina Guo published the DECIDE model of decision-making, which has six parts:<ref>{{cite journal |last=Guo |first=Kristina L. |date=June 2008 |title=DECIDE: a decision-making model for more effective decision making by health care managers |journal=The Health Care Manager |volume=27 |issue=2 |pages=118\u2013127 |doi=10.1097/01.HCM.0000285046.27290.90 |pmid=18475113 |ref=harv}}</ref>\n# '''D'''efine the problem\n# '''E'''stablish or '''E'''numerate all the criteria (constraints)\n# '''C'''onsider or '''C'''ollect all the alternatives\n# '''I'''dentify the best alternative\n# '''D'''evelop and implement a [[Action plan|plan of action]]\n# [[Evaluation|'''E'''valuate]] and [[wikt:monitoring|monitor]] the solution and examine [[feedback]] when necessary\n\n===Other===\nIn 2007, Pam Brown of [[Singleton Hospital]] in [[Swansea]], [[Wales]], divided the decision-making process into seven steps:<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.pulsetoday.co.uk/career-coach-decision-making/10967084.article |last=Brown |first=Pam |title=Career coach: decision-making |publisher=Pulse |date=November 29, 2007 |accessdate=July 12, 2012}} {{subscription}}</ref>\n\n# Outline the goal and outcome.\n# Gather data.\n# Develop alternatives (i.e., brainstorming).\n# List pros and cons of each alternative.\n# Make the decision.\n# Immediately take action to implement it.\n# Learn from and reflect on the decision.\n\nIn 2009, professor John Pijanowski described how the Arkansas Program, an ethics curriculum at the [[University of Arkansas]], used eight stages of [[Morality|moral]] decision-making based on the work of [[James Rest]]:<ref>{{cite journal |last=Pijanowski |first=John |date=February 2009 |title=The role of learning theory in building effective college ethics curricula |journal=Journal of College and Character |volume=10 |issue=3 |pages=1\u201313 |doi=10.2202/1940-1639.1088 }}</ref>{{rp|6}}\n# Establishing community: Create and nurture the relationships, norms, and procedures that will influence how problems are understood and communicated. This stage takes place prior to and during a moral dilemma.\n# Perception: Recognize that a problem exists.\n# Interpretation: Identify competing explanations for the problem, and evaluate the drivers behind those interpretations.\n# Judgment: Sift through various possible actions or responses and determine which is more justifiable.\n# Motivation: Examine the competing commitments which may distract from a more moral course of action and then prioritize and commit to moral values over other personal, institutional or social values.\n# Action: Follow through with action that supports the more justified decision.\n# Reflection in action.\n# Reflection on action.\n\n===Group stages===\n\nAccording to B. Aubrey Fisher, there are four stages or phases that should be involved in all group decision-making:<ref>{{cite book |last=Griffin |first=Emory A. |date=1991 |chapter=Interact system model of decision emergence of B. Aubrey Fisher |title=A first look at communication theory |location=New York |publisher=[[McGraw-Hill]] |edition=1st |pages=253\u2013262 |isbn=978-0070227781 |oclc=21973427 |chapterurl=http://www.afirstlook.com/docs/intersys.pdf}}</ref>\n* Orientation. Members meet for the first time and start to get to know each other.\n* Conflict. Once group members become familiar with each other, disputes, little fights and arguments occur. Group members eventually work it out.\n* Emergence. The group begins to clear up vague opinions by talking about them.\n* [[Reinforcement]]. Members finally make a decision and provide justification for it.\n\nIt is said that establishing critical norms in a group improves the quality of decisions, while the majority of opinions (called consensus norms) do not.<ref>{{cite journal |last=Postmes |first=T |title=Quality of decision making and group norms |journal=[[Journal of Personality and Social Psychology]] |year=2001 |volume=80 |issue=6 |pages=918\u2013930 |doi=10.1037/0022-3514.80.6.918 |url=http://psycnet.apa.org/journals/psp/80/6/918/ |last2=Spears |first2=Russell |last3=Cihangir |first3=Sezgin |pmid=11414374}}</ref>\n\nConflicts in socialization are divided in to functional and dysfunctional types. Functional conflicts are mostly the questioning the managers assumptions in their decision making and dysfunctional conflicts are like personal attacks and every action which decrease team effectiveness. Functional conflicts are the better ones to gain higher quality decision making caused by the increased team knowledge and shared understanding.<ref>Brockmann, E., Anthony, W., 2002. Tacit knowledge and strategic decision making. Group & Organization Management. Vol. 27 (4), 436\u2013455. {{doi|10.1177/1059601102238356}}</ref>\n\n== Rational and irrational ==\n\nIn [[economics]], it is thought that if humans are rational and free to make their own decisions, then they would behave according to [[rational choice theory]].<ref name=\"Schacter2011\">{{cite book |last1=Schacter |first1=Daniel L. |authorlink1=Daniel Schacter |last2=Gilbert |first2=Daniel Todd |authorlink2=Daniel Gilbert (psychologist) |last3=Wegner |first3=Daniel M. |authorlink3=Daniel Wegner |date=2011 |origyear=2009 |title=Psychology |url=https://archive.org/details/psychology0000scha |url-access=registration |edition=2nd |location=New York |publisher=Worth Publishers |isbn=9781429237192 |oclc=755079969}}</ref>{{rp|368\u2013370}} Rational choice theory says that a person consistently makes choices that lead to the best situation for himself or herself, taking into account all available considerations including costs and benefits; the rationality of these considerations is from the point of view of the person himself, so a decision is not irrational just because someone else finds it questionable.\n\nIn reality, however, there are some factors that affect decision-making abilities and cause people to make irrational decisions{{spaced ndash}}for example, to make contradictory choices when faced with the same problem [[framing (social sciences)|framed]] in two different ways (see also [[Allais paradox]]).\n\nOne of the most prominent theories of decision making is [[subjective expected utility]] (SEU) theory, which describes the rational behavior of the decision maker.<ref name=\"Crozier\">{{cite book |last1=Crozier |first1=W. Ray |last2=Ranyard |first2=Rob |date=1997 |chapter=Cognitive process models and explanations of decision making |editor1-last=Ranyard |editor1-first=Rob |editor2-last=Crozier |editor2-first=W. Ray |editor3-last=Svenson |editor3-first=Ola |title=Decision making: cognitive models and explanations |series=Frontiers of cognitive science |location=London; New York |publisher=[[Routledge]] |pages=5\u201320 |isbn=978-0415158183 |oclc=37043834}}</ref> The decision maker assesses different alternatives by their utilities and the subjective probability of occurrence.<ref name=\"Crozier\"/>\n\nRational decision-making is often grounded on experience and theories exist that are able to put this approach on solid mathematical grounds so that subjectivity is reduced to a minimum, see e.g. [[scenario optimization]].\n\n== In adolescents vs. adults ==\n{{More citations needed section|date=May 2014}}\n\nDuring their adolescent years, teens are known for their high-risk behaviors and rash decisions. Recent research{{citation needed|date=January 2014}} has shown that there are differences in cognitive processes between adolescents and adults during decision-making. Researchers have concluded that differences in decision-making are not due to a lack of logic or reasoning, but more due to the immaturity of [[psychosocial]] capacities that influence decision-making. Examples of their undeveloped capacities which influence decision-making would be impulse control, emotion regulation, [[delayed gratification]] and resistance to [[peer pressure]]. In the past, researchers have thought that adolescent behavior was simply due to incompetency regarding decision-making. Currently, researchers have concluded that adults and adolescents are both competent decision-makers, not just adults. However, adolescents' competent decision-making skills decrease when psychosocial capacities become present.\n\nRecent research{{citation needed|date=January 2014}} has shown that risk-taking behaviors in adolescents may be the product of interactions between the socioemotional brain network and its [[Executive functions|cognitive-control network]]. The socioemotional part of the brain processes social and emotional stimuli and has been shown to be important in [[Reward system|reward processing]]. The cognitive-control network assists in planning and self-regulation. Both of these sections of the brain change over the course of [[puberty]]. However, the socioemotional network changes quickly and abruptly, while the cognitive-control network changes more gradually. Because of this difference in change, the cognitive-control network, which usually regulates the socioemotional network, struggles to control the socioemotional network when psychosocial capacities are present.{{clarify|date=January 2014}}\n\nWhen adolescents are exposed to social and emotional stimuli, their socioemotional network is activated as well as areas of the brain involved in reward processing. Because teens often gain a sense of reward from risk-taking behaviors, their repetition becomes ever more probable due to the reward experienced. In this, the process mirrors [[addiction]]. Teens can become addicted to risky behavior because they are in a high state of arousal and are rewarded for it not only by their own internal functions but also by their peers around them.\n\nAdults are generally better able to control their risk-taking because their cognitive-control system has matured enough to the point where it can control the socioemotional network, even in the context of high arousal or when psychosocial capacities are present. Also, adults are less likely to find themselves in situations that push them to do risky things. For example, teens are more likely to be around peers who peer pressure them into doing things, while adults are not as exposed to this sort of social setting.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Gardner|first1=Margo|last2=Steinberg|first2=Laurence|authorlink2=Laurence Steinberg|date=July 2005|title=Peer influence on risk taking, risk preference, and risky decision making in adolescence and adulthood: an experimental study|url=http://uwf.edu/smathews/documents/peerroleinrisktakinggardnerandsteinberg.pdf|journal=[[Developmental Psychology (journal)|Developmental Psychology]]|volume=41|issue=4|pages=625\u2013635|citeseerx=10.1.1.556.4973|doi=10.1037/0012-1649.41.4.625|pmid=16060809}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last=Steinberg|first=Laurence|authorlink=Laurence Steinberg|date=April 2007|title=Risk taking in adolescence: new perspectives from brain and behavioral science|journal=[[Current Directions in Psychological Science]]|volume=16|issue=2|pages=55\u201359|citeseerx=10.1.1.519.7099|doi=10.1111/j.1467-8721.2007.00475.x}}</ref>\n\nA recent study suggests that adolescents have difficulties adequately adjusting beliefs in response to bad news (such as reading that smoking poses a greater risk to health than they thought), but do not differ from adults in their ability to alter beliefs in response to good news.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Moutsiana|first1=Christina|last2=Garrett|first2=Neil|last3=Clarke|first3=Richard C.|last4=Lotto|first4=R. Beau|last5=Blakemore|first5=Sarah-Jayne|last6=Sharot|first6=Tali|date=October 2013|title=Human development of the ability to learn from bad news|journal=[[Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences]]|volume=110|issue=41|pages=16396\u201316401|doi=10.1073/pnas.1305631110|pmc=3799330|pmid=24019466}}</ref> This creates biased beliefs, which may lead to greater risk taking.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Reyna|first=Valerie F.|date=November 2013|title=Psychology: Good and bad news on the adolescent brain|journal=[[Nature (journal)|Nature]]|volume=503|issue=7474|pages=48\u201349|doi=10.1038/nature12704|pmid=24172899|ref=harv}}</ref>\n\n== Cognitive and personal biases ==\n\n[[Bias]]es usually affect decision-making processes. They appear more when decision task has time pressure, is done under high stress and/or task is highly complex.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=T|first=Maqsood|last2=A|first2=Finegan|last3=D|first3=Walker|date=2004|title=Biases and heuristics in judgment and decision making: The dark side of tacit knowledge|url=http://researchbank.rmit.edu.au/view/rmit:2008|journal=Issues in Informing Science and Information Technology|language=en|volume=1|issn=1547-5840}}</ref>\n\nHere is a list of commonly debated [[List of biases in judgment and decision-making|biases in judgment and decision-making]]:\n* Selective search for [[evidence]] (also known as [[confirmation bias]]): People tend to be willing to gather facts that support certain conclusions but disregard other facts that support different conclusions. Individuals who are highly defensive in this manner show significantly greater left prefrontal cortex activity as measured by [[Electroencephalography|EEG]] than do less defensive individuals.<ref>{{cite journal |last=Blackhart |first=G. C. |last2=Kline |first2=J. P. |year=2005 |title=Individual differences in anterior EEG asymmetry between high and low defensive individuals during a rumination/distraction task |journal=[[Personality and Individual Differences]] |volume=39 |issue=2 |pages=427\u2013437 |doi=10.1016/j.paid.2005.01.027 |url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/228480310}}</ref>\n* Premature termination of search for evidence: People tend to accept the first alternative that looks like it might work.\n* [[Cognitive inertia]] is the unwillingness to change existing thought patterns in the face of new circumstances.\n* Selective perception: People actively screen out information that they do not think is important (see also [[Prejudice]]). In one demonstration of this effect, discounting of arguments with which one disagrees (by judging them as untrue or irrelevant) was decreased by selective activation of right prefrontal cortex.<ref>{{cite journal |last=Drake |first=R. A. |year=1993 |title=Processing persuasive arguments: 2. Discounting of truth and relevance as a function of agreement and manipulated activation asymmetry |journal=[[Journal of Research in Personality]] |volume=27 |issue=2 |pages=184\u2013196 |doi=10.1006/jrpe.1993.1013}}</ref>\n* [[Wishful thinking]] is a tendency to want to see things in a certain{{spaced ndash}}usually positive{{spaced ndash}}light, which can distort perception and thinking.<ref>{{cite journal |last=Chua |first=E. F. |last2=Rand-Giovannetti |first2=E. |last3=Schacter |first3=D. L. |last4=Albert |first4=M. |last5=Sperling |first5=R. A. |year=2004 |title=Dissociating confidence and accuracy: Functional magnetic resonance imaging shows origins of the subjective memory experience |journal=[[Journal of Cognitive Neuroscience]] |volume=16 |issue=7 |pages=1131\u20131142 |doi=10.1162/0898929041920568 |pmid=15453969 |url=http://dash.harvard.edu/bitstream/handle/1/3627270/Schacter_DissociatingConfidence.pdf}}</ref>\n* [[Choice-supportive bias]] occurs when people distort their memories of chosen and rejected options to make the chosen options seem more attractive.\n* Recency: People tend to place more attention on more recent information and either ignore or forget more distant information (see [[Semantic priming]]). The opposite effect in the first set of data or other information is termed ''[[primacy effect]]''.<ref>{{cite book |last=Plous |first=Scott |date=1993 |title=The psychology of judgment and decision making |location=Philadelphia |publisher=[[Temple University Press]] |isbn=978-0877229131 |oclc=26548229 |ref=harv |url-access=registration |url=https://archive.org/details/thepsyc_plo_1993_00_3134 }}</ref>{{Page needed|date=July 2015}}\n* Repetition bias is a willingness to believe what one has been told most often and by the greatest number of different sources.\n* [[Anchoring and adjustment]]: Decisions are unduly influenced by initial information that shapes our view of subsequent information.\n* [[Groupthink]] is [[peer pressure]] to conform to the opinions held by the group.\n* Source credibility bias is a tendency to reject a person's statement on the basis of a bias against the person, organization, or group to which the person belongs. People preferentially accept statements by others that they like (see also [[Prejudice]]).\n* Incremental decision-making and escalating commitment: People look at a decision as a small step in a process, and this tends to perpetuate a series of similar decisions. This can be contrasted with ''zero-based decision-making'' (see [[Slippery slope]]).\n* [[Attribution theory|Attribution asymmetry]]: People tend to attribute their own success to internal factors, including abilities and talents, but explain their failures in terms of external factors such as bad luck. The reverse bias is shown when people explain others' success or failure.\n* Role fulfillment is a tendency to conform to others' decision-making expectations.\n* Underestimating [[uncertainty]] and the [[illusion of control]]: People tend to underestimate future uncertainty because of a tendency to believe they have more control over events than they really do.\n* [[Framing (social sciences)#Absolute and relative influences|Framing bias]]: This is best avoided by increasing [[numeracy]] and presenting data in several formats (for example, using both absolute and relative scales).<ref name=\"pmid21792695\">{{cite journal |last1=Perneger |first1=Thomas V. |last2=Agoritsas |first2=Thomas |date=December 2011 |title=Doctors and patients' susceptibility to framing bias: a randomized trial |journal=[[Journal of General Internal Medicine]] |volume=26 |issue=12 |pages=1411\u20131417 |doi=10.1007/s11606-011-1810-x |pmid=21792695 |ref=harv |pmc=3235613}}</ref>\n** [[Sunk-cost fallacy]] is a specific type of framing effect that affects decision-making. It involves an individual making a decision about a current situation based on what they have previously invested in the situation.<ref name=\"Schacter2011\"/>{{rp|372}} An example of this would be an individual that is refraining from dropping a class that they are most likely to fail, due to the fact that they feel as though they have done so much work in the course thus far.\n* [[Prospect theory]] involves the idea that when faced with a decision-making event, an individual is more likely to take on a risk when evaluating potential losses, and are more likely to avoid risks when evaluating potential gains. This can influence one's decision-making depending if the situation entails a threat, or opportunity.<ref name=\"Schacter2011\"/>{{rp|373}}\n* [[Optimism bias]] is a tendency to overestimate the likelihood of positive events occurring in the future and underestimate the likelihood of negative life events.<ref>{{cite book |last=Sharot |first=Tali |date=2011 |title=The optimism bias: a tour of the irrationally positive brain |edition=1st |location=New York |publisher=[[Pantheon Books]] |isbn=9780307378484 |oclc=667609433}}</ref> Such biased expectations are generated and maintained in the face of counter-evidence through a tendency to discount undesirable information.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Sharot |first1=Tali |last2=Korn |first2=Christoph W. |last3=Dolan |first3=Raymond J. |date=October 2011 |title=How unrealistic optimism is maintained in the face of reality |journal=[[Nature Neuroscience]] |volume=14 |issue=11 |pages=1475\u20131479 |doi=10.1038/nn.2949 |pmid=21983684 |pmc=3204264}}</ref> An optimism bias can alter risk perception and decision-making in many domains, ranging from finance to health.\n* [[Reference class forecasting]] was developed to eliminate or reduce cognitive biases in decision-making.\n\n== Cognitive limitations in groups ==\n{{Main|Group decision-making#Group discussion pitfalls}}\nIn groups, people generate decisions through active and complex processes. One method consists of three steps: initial preferences are expressed by members; the members of the group then gather and share information concerning those preferences; finally, the members combine their views and make a single choice about how to face the problem. Although these steps are relatively ordinary, judgements are often distorted by cognitive and motivational biases, include \"sins of commission\", \"sins of omission\", and \"sins of imprecision\".<ref name=\"Group Dynamics\">{{cite book|authorlink1=Donelson R. Forsyth |last=Forsyth |first=Donelson R. |date=2014 |origyear=1983 |title=Group dynamics |edition=6th |location=Belmont, CA |publisher=[[Wadsworth Cengage Learning]] |isbn=9781133956532 |oclc=826872491}}</ref>{{Page needed|date=April 2017}}\n\n== Cognitive styles ==\n\n===Optimizing vs. satisficing===\n{{main|Maximization (psychology)}}\n\n[[Herbert A. Simon]] coined the phrase \"[[bounded rationality]]\" to express the idea that human decision-making is limited by available information, available time and the mind's information-processing ability. Further psychological research has identified individual differences between two cognitive styles: ''[[Maximization (psychology)|maximizers]]'' try to make an [[optimal decision]], whereas ''[[satisficer]]s'' simply try to find a solution that is \"good enough\". Maximizers tend to take longer making decisions due to the need to maximize performance across all variables and make tradeoffs carefully; they also tend to more often regret their decisions (perhaps because they are more able than satisficers to recognize that a decision turned out to be sub-optimal).<ref>{{cite book |last=Sparks |first=Erin |date=2007 |chapter=Satisficing |editor1-last=Baumeister |editor1-first=Roy F. |editor1-link=Roy Baumeister |editor2-last=Vohs |editor2-first=Kathleen D. |title=Encyclopedia of social psychology |location=Thousand Oaks, CA |publisher=[[Sage Publications]] |pages=776\u2013778 |isbn=9781412916707 |oclc=123119782 |chapterurl=https://books.google.com/books?id=CQBzAwAAQBAJ&pg=PT926}}</ref>\n\n===Intuitive vs. rational===\n{{Main|Dual process theory}}\n\nThe psychologist [[Daniel Kahneman]], adopting terms originally proposed by the psychologists [[Keith Stanovich]] and Richard West, has theorized that a person's decision-making is the result of an interplay between two kinds of [[cognitive process]]es: an automatic intuitive system (called \"System 1\") and an effortful rational system (called \"System 2\"). System 1 is a bottom-up, fast, and implicit system of decision-making, while system 2 is a top-down, slow, and explicit system of decision-making.<ref>{{cite book |last=Kahneman |first=Daniel |authorlink=Daniel Kahneman |date=2011 |title=Thinking, fast and slow |location=New York |publisher=[[Farrar, Straus, and Giroux]] |isbn=9780374275631 |oclc=706020998}}</ref> System 1 includes simple [[heuristics in judgment and decision-making]] such as the [[affect heuristic]], the [[availability heuristic]], the [[familiarity heuristic]], and the [[representativeness heuristic]].\n\n===Combinatorial vs. positional===\n\nStyles and methods of decision-making were elaborated by [[Aron Katsenelinboigen]], the founder of [[predispositioning theory]]. In his analysis on styles and methods, Katsenelinboigen referred to the game of chess, saying that \"chess does disclose various methods of operation, notably the creation of predisposition-methods which may be applicable to other, more complex systems.\"<ref name=\"Concept of Indeterminism\">{{cite book |last=Katsenelinboigen |first=Aron |authorlink=Aron Katsenelinboigen |date=1997 |title=The concept of indeterminism and its applications: economics, social systems, ethics, artificial intelligence, and aesthetics |location=Westport, CT |publisher=Praeger |isbn=978-0275957889 |oclc=36438766 |url=http://aronkatsenelinboigen.net/CONCEPT_OF_INDETERMINISM.PDF |access-date=2015-07-27 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110723015801/http://aronkatsenelinboigen.net/CONCEPT_OF_INDETERMINISM.PDF |archive-date=2011-07-23 |url-status=dead }}</ref>{{rp|5}}\n\nKatsenelinboigen states that apart from the methods (reactive and selective) and sub-methods (randomization, predispositioning, programming), there are two major styles: positional and combinational. Both styles are utilized in the game of chess. According to Katsenelinboigen, the two styles reflect two basic approaches to [[uncertainty]]: deterministic (combinational style) and indeterministic (positional style). Katsenelinboigen's definition of the two styles are the following.\n\nThe combinational style is characterized by:\n* a very narrow, clearly defined, primarily material goal; and\n* a program that links the initial position with the final outcome.\n\nIn defining the combinational style in chess, Katsenelinboigen wrote: \"The combinational style features a clearly formulated limited objective, namely the capture of material (the main constituent element of a chess position). The objective is implemented via a well-defined, and in some cases, unique sequence of moves aimed at reaching the set goal. As a rule, this sequence leaves no options for the opponent. Finding a combinational objective allows the player to focus all his energies on efficient execution, that is, the player's analysis may be limited to the pieces directly partaking in the combination. This approach is the crux of the combination and the combinational style of play.<ref name=\"Concept of Indeterminism\"/>{{rp|57}}\n\nThe positional style is distinguished by:\n* a positional goal; and\n* a formation of semi-complete linkages between the initial step and final outcome.\n\n\"Unlike the combinational player, the positional player is occupied, first and foremost, with the elaboration of the position that will allow him to develop in the unknown future. In playing the positional style, the player must evaluate relational and material parameters as independent variables. ... The positional style gives the player the opportunity to develop a position until it becomes pregnant with a combination. However, the combination is not the final goal of the positional player{{spaced ndash}}it helps him to achieve the desirable, keeping in mind a predisposition for the future development. The [[pyrrhic victory]] is the best example of one's inability to think positionally.\"<ref>{{cite book |last=Ulea |first=Vera |date=2002 |title=A concept of dramatic genre and the comedy of a new type: chess, literature, and film |location=Carbondale |publisher=[[Southern Illinois University Press]] |isbn=978-0809324521 |oclc=51301095 |pages=[https://books.google.com/books?id=QPWAkw_k5PkC&pg=PA17 17\u201318]}}</ref>\n\nThe positional style serves to:\n* create a predisposition to the future development of the position;\n* induce the environment in a certain way;\n* absorb an unexpected outcome in one's favor; and\n* avoid the negative aspects of unexpected outcomes.\n\n===Influence of Myers-Briggs type===\n\nAccording to [[Isabel Briggs Myers]], a person's decision-making process depends to a significant degree on their cognitive style.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Myers |first1=Isabel Briggs |authorlink1=Isabel Briggs Myers  |last2=Kirby |first2=Linda K. |last3=Myers |first3=Katharine D. |date=1998 |origyear=1976 |title=Introduction to type: a guide to understanding your results on the Myers-Briggs Type Indicator |edition=6th |series=Introduction to type series |location=Palo Alto, CA |publisher=Consulting Psychologists Press |oclc=40336039}}</ref>{{Page needed|date=July 2015}} Myers developed a set of four bi-polar dimensions, called the [[Myers-Briggs Type Indicator]] (MBTI). The terminal points on these dimensions are: ''thinking'' and ''feeling''; ''extroversion'' and ''introversion''; ''judgment'' and ''perception''; and ''sensing'' and ''intuition''. She claimed that a person's decision-making style correlates well with how they score on these four dimensions. For example, someone who scored near the thinking, extroversion, sensing, and judgment ends of the dimensions would tend to have a logical, analytical, objective, critical, and empirical decision-making style. However, some psychologists say that the MBTI lacks reliability and validity and is poorly constructed.<ref>{{cite journal |last=Pittenger |first=David J. |date=2005 |title=Cautionary comments regarding the Myers-Briggs Type Indicator |journal=[[Consulting Psychology Journal: Practice and Research]] |volume=57 |issue=3 |pages=210\u2013221 |doi=10.1037/1065-9293.57.3.210 |url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/232494957}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last=Hogan |first=Robert |authorlink=Robert Hogan (psychologist) |date=2007 |title=Personality and the fate of organizations |location=Mahwah, NJ |publisher=[[Lawrence Erlbaum Associates]] |isbn=978-0805841428 |oclc=65400436 |page=28 |quote=Most personality psychologists regard the MBTI as little more than an elaborate Chinese fortune cookie...}}</ref>\n\nOther studies suggest that these national or [[cross-cultural differences in decision-making]] exist across entire societies. For example, [[Maris Martinsons]] has found that American, Japanese and Chinese business leaders each exhibit a distinctive national style of decision-making.<ref>{{cite journal |last=Martinsons |first=Maris G. |date=December 2006 |title=Comparing the decision styles of American, Chinese and Japanese business leaders |publisher=Best Paper Proceedings of [[Academy of Management]] Meetings, Washington, DC, August 2001 |ssrn=952292 }}</ref>\n\nThe Myers-Briggs typology has been the subject of criticism regarding its poor psychometric properties. <ref>{{Cite journal|last=Pittenger|first=David|date=1993|title=\"Measuring the MBTI ... And Coming Up Short\"|url=http://www.indiana.edu/~jobtalk/HRMWebsite/hrm/articles/develop/mbti.pdf|journal=Journal of Career Planning and Employment.|volume=54 (1)|pages=48\u201352.|via=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Schuwirth|first=Lambert|last2=Cantillon|first2=Peter|date=2004-05-22|title=What the educators are saying|url=http://www.bmj.com/lookup/doi/10.1136/bmj.328.7450.1244|journal=BMJ|language=en|volume=328|issue=7450|pages=1244|doi=10.1136/bmj.328.7450.1244|issn=0959-8138}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Pittenger|first=David J.|date=2005|title=Cautionary comments regarding the Myers-Briggs Type Indicator.|url=http://dx.doi.org/10.1037/1065-9293.57.3.210|journal=Consulting Psychology Journal: Practice and Research|volume=57|issue=3|pages=210\u2013221|doi=10.1037/1065-9293.57.3.210|issn=1939-0149}}</ref>\n\n=== General decision-making style (GDMS) ===\nIn the general decision-making style (GDMS) test developed by Suzanne Scott and Reginald Bruce, there are five decision-making styles: rational, intuitive, dependent, avoidant, and spontaneous.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Scott |first1=Susanne G. |last2=Bruce |first2=Reginald A. |date=1995 |title=Decision-making style: the development and assessment of a new measure |journal=[[Educational and Psychological Measurement]] |volume=55 |issue=5 |pages=818\u2013831 |doi=10.1177/0013164495055005017}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last=Thunholm |first=Peter |date=March 2004 |title=Decision-making style: habit, style or both? |journal=[[Personality and Individual Differences]] |volume=36 |issue=4 |pages=931\u2013944 |doi=10.1016/S0191-8869(03)00162-4}}</ref> These five different decision-making styles change depending on the context and situation, and one style is not necessarily better than any other. In the examples below, the individual is working for a company and is offered a job from a different company.\n* The ''rational'' style is an in-depth search for, and a strong consideration of, other options and/or information prior to making a decision. In this style, the individual would research the new job being offered, review their current job, and look at the pros and cons of taking the new job versus staying with their current company.\n* The ''intuitive'' style is confidence in one's initial feelings and gut reactions. In this style, if the individual initially prefers the new job because they have a feeling that the work environment is better suited for them, then they would decide to take the new job. The individual might not make this decision as soon as the job is offered.\n* The ''dependent'' style is asking for other people's input and instructions on what decision should be made. In this style, the individual could ask friends, family, coworkers, etc., but the individual might not ask all of these people.\n* The ''avoidant'' style is averting the responsibility of making a decision. In this style, the individual would not make a decision. Therefore, the individual would stick with their current job.\n* The ''spontaneous'' style is a need to make a decision as soon as possible rather than waiting to make a decision. In this style, the individual would either reject or accept the job as soon as it is offered.\n\n== Organizational vs. individual level ==\nThere are a few characteristics that differentiate organizational decision-making from individual decision-making as studied in lab experiments <ref>Shapira, Z. (2002). \"Organizational Decision Making. Cambridge Series on Judgment and Decision Making\", Cambridge University Press: pp.4-6. {{ISBN|0521890500}}, 9780521890502 </ref>:\n\n1. Unlike most lab studies of individual decision-making, ''ambiguity'' is pervasive in organizations. There is often only ambiguous information, and there is ambiguity about preferences as well as about interpreting the history of decisions.\n\n2. Decision-making in and by organizations is embedded in a ''longitudinal'' context, meaning that participants in organizational decision-making are a part of ongoing processes. Even if they don't take on active roles in all phases of decision-making, they are part of the Decision Process and its consequences. Decisions in organizations are made in a sequential manner, and commitment may be more important in such processes than judgmental accuracy. In contrast, most lab studies of individual decision-making are conducted in artificial settings (lab) that are not connected to the subjects\u2019 ongoing activities.\n\n3. ''Incentives'' play an important role in organizational decision-making. Incentives, penalties, and their ramifications are real and may have long-lasting effects. These effects are intensified due to the longitudinal nature of decision-making in organizational settings. Incentives and penalties are very salient in organizations, and often they command managerial attention.\n\n4. Many executives, especially in middle management, may make ''repeated decisions'' on similar issues. Managers may develop a sense of using his/her skills (which may be faulty) and a sense of having control and using one's skills are pervasive in managerial thinking about risk taking. Several repeated decisions are made by following rules rather than by using pure information processing modes.\n\n5. ''Conflict'' is pervasive in organizational decision-making. Many times power considerations and agenda setting determine decisions rather than calculations based on the decision's parameters. The nature of authority relations may have a large impact on the way decisions are made in organizations, which are basically political systems.\n\n== See also ==\n{{Portal|Philosophy|Psychology}}\n{{Library resources box |by=no |onlinebooks=no |others=no |about=yes |label=Decision-making}}\n{{div col|colwidth=22em}}\n* [[Aboulomania]]\n* [[Adaptive performance]]\n* [[Agent (economics)]]\n* [[Analytic hierarchy process]]\n* [[Argument map]]\n* [[Business decision mapping]]\n* [[Choice architecture]]\n* [[Choice modelling]]\n* [[Concept driven strategy]]\n* [[Decision downloading]]\n* [[Decision fatigue]]\n* [[Decision quality]]\n* [[Decision-making unit]]\n* [[Foresight (psychology)]]\n* [[Framing (social sciences)]]\n* [[Free will]]\n* [[Idea networking]]\n* [[Robust decision]]\n{{div col end}}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n{{Systems engineering}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Decision-Making}}\n[[Category:Decision-making| ]]\n[[Category:Neuropsychological assessment]]\n[[Category:Unsolved problems in neuroscience]]\n[[Category:Analysis]]\n[[Category:Prediction]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Cognitive process resulting in choosing a course of action}}\n{{about|decision making as analyzed in psychology|a broader discipline|Decision theory}}\n[[File:Wikipedia article-creation-2.svg|thumb|Sample [[flowchart]] representing a decision process to add a new article to Wikipedia.]]\n\nIn [[psychology]], '''decision-making''' (also spelled '''decision making''' and '''decisionmaking''') is regarded as the [[Cognition|cognitive process]] resulting in the selection of a belief or a course of action among several alternative possibilities. Decision-making is the process of identifying and choosing alternatives based on the [[value (ethics)|values]], [[preference]]s and beliefs of the decision-maker. Every decision-making process produces a final [[choice]], which may or may not prompt action.\n\nResearch about decision-making is also published under the label [[problem solving]], in particular in European [[psychological research]].<ref>{{cite book|title=Complex problem solving: the European perspective|date=1995|publisher=[[Lawrence Erlbaum Associates]]|isbn=978-0805813364|editor1-last=Frensch|editor1-first=Peter A.|location=Hillsdale, NJ|oclc=32131412|editor2-last=Funke|editor2-first=Joachim}}</ref>\n\n==Overview==\nDecision-making can be regarded as a problem-solving activity yielding a solution deemed to be optimal, or at least satisfactory. It is therefore a process which can be more or less [[Rationality|rational]] or [[Irrationality|irrational]] and can be based on [[explicit knowledge|explicit]] or [[tacit knowledge]] and beliefs. Tacit knowledge is often used to fill the gaps in complex decision making processes.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Brockmann |first1=Erich N. |last2=Anthony |first2=William P. |date=December 2016 |title=Tacit knowledge and strategic decision making |journal=[[Group & Organization Management]] |volume=27 |issue=4 |pages=436\u2013455 |doi=10.1177/1059601102238356}}</ref> Usually both of these types of knowledge, tacit and explicit, are used together in the decision-making process.\n\nHuman performance has been the subject of active research from several perspectives:\n* [[Psychology|Psychological]]: examining individual decisions in the context of a set of needs, preferences and values the individual has or seeks.\n* [[Cognition|Cognitive]]: the decision-making process regarded as a continuous process integrated in the interaction with the environment.\n* [[Normative]]: the analysis of individual decisions concerned with the logic of decision-making, or [[communicative rationality]], and the invariant choice it leads to.<ref name=\"Kahneman\">{{cite book |editor1-last=Kahneman |editor1-first=Daniel |editor1-link=Daniel Kahneman |editor2-last=Tversky |editor2-first=Amos |editor2-link=Amos Tversky |date=2000 |title=Choices, values, and frames |location=New York; Cambridge, UK |publisher=[[Russell Sage Foundation]]; [[Cambridge University Press]] |isbn=978-0521621724 |oclc=42934579 |page=[https://books.google.com/books?id=P5GsREMbUmAC&pg=PA211 211]}}</ref>\n\nA major part of decision-making involves the analysis of a finite set of alternatives described in terms of evaluative criteria. Then the task might be to rank these alternatives in terms of how attractive they are to the decision-maker(s) when all the criteria are considered simultaneously. Another task might be to find the best alternative or to determine the relative total priority of each alternative (for instance, if alternatives represent projects competing for funds) when all the criteria are considered simultaneously. Solving such problems is the focus of [[multiple-criteria decision analysis]] (MCDA). This area of decision-making, although very old, has attracted the interest of many researchers and practitioners and is still highly debated as there are many MCDA methods which may yield very different results when they are applied on exactly the same data.<ref name=MCDM>{{cite book |last=Triantaphyllou |first=Evangelos |title=Multi-criteria decision making methods: a comparative study |volume=44 |publisher=[[Kluwer Academic Publishers]] |series=Applied optimization |year=2000 |location=Dordrecht, Netherlands |page=320 |url=http://www.csc.lsu.edu/trianta/Books/DecisionMaking1/Book1.htm |isbn=978-0792366072 |doi=10.1007/978-1-4757-3157-6}}</ref> This leads to the formulation of a [[decision-making paradox]]. [[Logic]]al decision-making is an important part of all science-based professions, where specialists apply their [[knowledge]] in a given area to make informed decisions. For example, medical decision-making often involves a [[Medical diagnosis|diagnosis]] and the selection of appropriate treatment. But [[naturalistic decision-making]] research shows that in situations with higher time pressure, higher stakes, or increased ambiguities, experts may use [[Intuition (psychology)|intuitive]] decision-making rather than structured approaches. They may follow a [[recognition primed decision]] that fits their experience and arrive at a course of action without weighing alternatives.{{citation needed|date=January 2014}}\n\nThe decision-maker's environment can play a part in the decision-making process. For example, environmental complexity is a factor that influences cognitive function.<ref name=\"necsi.edu\">{{cite book |last1=Davidson |first1=Alice Ware |last2=Bar-Yam |first2=Yaneer |date=2006 |origyear=2000 |chapter=Environmental complexity: information for human\u2013environment well-being |editor1-last=Bar-Yam |editor1-first=Yaneer |editor2-last=Minai |editor2-first=Ali |title=Unifying themes in complex systems |location=Berlin; New York |publisher=Springer |pages=157\u2013168 |isbn=9783540358640 |doi=10.1007/978-3-540-35866-4_16 |chapterurl=http://necsi.edu/projects/yaneer/envcomplexity00.pdf|citeseerx=10.1.1.33.7118 }}</ref> A complex environment is an environment with a large number of different possible states which come and go over time.<ref name=\"its.caltech.edu\">{{cite book |last=Godfrey-Smith |first=Peter |authorlink=Peter Godfrey-Smith |date=2001 |chapter=Environmental complexity and the evolution of cognition |editor1-last=Sternberg |editor1-first=Robert J. |editor1-link=Robert Sternberg |editor2-last=Kaufman |editor2-first=James C. |editor2-link=James C. Kaufman |title=The evolution of intelligence |location=Mahwah, NJ |publisher=[[Lawrence Erlbaum Associates]] |pages=223\u2013250 |isbn=978-0805832679 |oclc=44775038 |chapterurl=http://www.its.caltech.edu/~theory/Godfrey-Smith.pdf}}</ref> Studies done at the [[University of Colorado]] have shown that more complex environments correlate with higher cognitive function, which means that a decision can be influenced by the location. One experiment measured complexity in a room by the number of small objects and appliances present; a simple room had less of those things. Cognitive function was greatly affected by the higher measure of environmental complexity making it easier to think about the situation and make a better decision.<ref name=\"necsi.edu\"/>\n\n== Problem analysis ==\n{{More citations needed section|date=July 2015}}\n\nIt is important to differentiate between [[problem analysis]] and decision-making. Traditionally, it is argued that problem analysis must be done first, so that the information gathered in that process may be used towards decision-making.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Kepner |first1=Charles Higgins |last2=Tregoe |first2=Benjamin B. |authorlink2=Benjamin Tregoe |date=1997 |origyear=1965 |title=The new rational manager: an updated edition for a new world |edition=Updated |location=Princeton, NJ |publisher=Princeton Research Press |oclc=37666447 |ref=harv}}</ref>{{Page needed|date=July 2015}}\n\n; Characteristics of problem analysis:\n* Problems are merely deviations from performance standards\n* Problems must be precisely identified and described\n* Problems are caused by a change from a distinctive feature\n* Something can always be used to distinguish between what has and hasn't been affected by a cause\n* Causes of problems can be deduced from relevant changes found in analyzing the problem\n* Most likely cause of a problem is the one that exactly explains all the facts, while having the fewest (or weakest) assumptions ([[Occam's razor]]).\n\n; Characteristics of decision-making:\n* Objectives must first be established\n* Objectives must be classified and placed in order of importance\n* Alternative actions must be developed\n* The alternatives must be evaluated against all the objectives\n* The alternative that is able to achieve all the objectives is the tentative decision\n* The tentative decision is evaluated for more possible consequences\n* The decisive actions are taken, and additional actions are taken to prevent any adverse consequences from becoming problems and starting both systems (problem analysis and decision-making) all over again\n* There are steps that are generally followed that result in a decision model that can be used to determine an optimal production plan<ref>{{cite book |last=Monahan |first=George E. |date=2000 |title=Management decision making: spreadsheet modeling, analysis, and application |location=Cambridge, UK; New York |publisher=[[Cambridge University Press]] |isbn=978-0521781183 |oclc=42921287 |pages=[https://books.google.com/books?id=kOAKlA-PJTkC&pg=PA33 33\u201340]}}</ref>\n* In a situation featuring conflict, [[role-playing]] may be helpful for predicting decisions to be made by involved parties<ref>{{cite book |last=Armstrong |first=Jon Scott |date=2001 |chapter=Role playing: a method to forecast decisions |editor-last=Armstrong |editor-first=Jon Scott |title=Principles of forecasting: a handbook for researchers and practitioners |volume=30 |series=International series in operations research & management science |location=Boston, MA |publisher=[[Kluwer Academic Publishers]] |pages=15\u201330 |isbn=978-0792379300 |doi=10.1007/978-0-306-47630-3_2|citeseerx=10.1.1.464.5677 }}</ref>\n\n===Analysis paralysis===\n{{Main|Analysis paralysis}}\n\n[[Analysis paralysis]] is the state of over-analyzing (or over-thinking) a situation so that a decision or action is never taken, in effect paralyzing the outcome.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://en.oxforddictionaries.com/definition/us/analysis_paralysis|title=analysis paralysis {{!}} Definition of analysis paralysis in US English by Oxford Dictionaries|website=Oxford Dictionaries {{!}} English|access-date=2018-11-10}}</ref>\n\n===Information overload===\n{{Main|Information overload}}\n\nInformation overload is \"a gap between the volume of information and the tools we have to assimilate\" it.<ref>[[Paul Saffo]] quoted in: {{cite magazine |url=http://www.informationweek.com/551/51mtinf.htm |date=30 October 1995 |title=Managing information: infoglut |last=Foley |first=John |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20010222082946/http://www.informationweek.com/551/51mtinf.htm |archivedate=2001-02-22 |accessdate=2015-07-26 |magazine=[[InformationWeek]]}}</ref> Information used in decision making is to reduce or eliminate uncertainty.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Duncan|date=1972|title=Characteristics of organizational environments and perceived environment uncertainty|url=|journal=Administrative Science Quarterly|volume=17|issue=3|pages=313\u201327|doi=10.2307/2392145|jstor=2392145}}</ref> Excessive information affects problem processing and tasking, which affects decision-making.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Kutty |first1=Ambalika D. |last2=Kumar Shee |first2=Himanshu |last3=Pathak |first3=R. D. |date=November 2007 |title=Decision-making: too much info! |journal=Monash Business Review |volume=3 |issue=3 |pages=8\u20139 |doi=10.2104/mbr07056 |url=http://arrow.monash.edu.au/hdl/1959.1/787807 }}{{Dead link|date=July 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> Crystal C. Hall and colleagues described an \"illusion of knowledge\", which means that as individuals encounter too much knowledge it can interfere with their ability to make rational decisions.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Hall |first1=Crystal C. |last2=Ariss |first2=Lynn |last3=Todorov |first3=Alexander |date=July 2007 |title=The illusion of knowledge: when more information reduces accuracy and increases confidence |journal=Organizational Behavior and Human Decision Processes |volume=103 |issue=2 |pages=277\u2013290 |doi=10.1016/j.obhdp.2007.01.003 |url=http://courses.washington.edu/pbafhall/514/514%20Readings/Hall-OBHDP.pdf}}</ref>\n\n===Post-decision analysis===\n\nEvaluation and analysis of past decisions is complementary to decision-making. See also [[Mental accounting]] and [[Postmortem documentation]].\n\n== Neuroscience ==\n\nDecision-making is a region of intense study in the fields of [[systems neuroscience]], and [[cognitive neuroscience]]. Several brain structures, including the [[anterior cingulate cortex]] (ACC), [[orbitofrontal cortex]] and the overlapping [[ventromedial prefrontal cortex]] are believed to be involved in decision-making processes. A [[neuroimaging]] study<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Walton|first1=Mark E.|last2=Devlin|first2=Joseph T.|last3=Rushworth|first3=Matthew F. S.|date=November 2004|title=Interactions between decision making and performance monitoring within prefrontal cortex|journal=[[Nature Neuroscience]]|volume=7|issue=11|pages=1259\u20131265|doi=10.1038/nn1339|pmid=15494729}}</ref> found distinctive patterns of neural activation in these regions depending on whether decisions were made on the basis of perceived personal [[Volition (psychology)|volition]] or following directions from someone else. Patients with damage to the [[ventromedial prefrontal cortex]] have difficulty making advantageous decisions.<ref>{{cite book|title=Descartes' error: emotion, reason, and the human brain|last=Damasio|first=Antonio R.|date=1994|publisher=Putnam|isbn=978-0399138942|location=New York|oclc=30780083|authorlink=Antonio Damasio|url=https://archive.org/details/descarteserrorem00dama}}</ref>{{Page needed|date=July 2015}}\n\nA common laboratory paradigm for studying neural decision-making is the [[two-alternative forced choice]] task (2AFC), in which a subject has to choose between two alternatives within a certain time. A study of a [[two-alternative forced choice]] task involving [[rhesus monkey]]s found that neurons in the [[parietal cortex]] not only represent the formation of a decision<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Gold|first1=Joshua I.|last2=Shadlen|first2=Michael N.|date=2007|title=The neural basis of decision making|journal=Annual Review of Neuroscience|volume=30|pages=535\u2013574|doi=10.1146/annurev.neuro.29.051605.113038|pmid=17600525}}</ref> but also signal the degree of certainty (or \"confidence\") associated with the decision.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Kiani|first1=Roozbeh|last2=Shadlen|first2=Michael N.|date=May 2009|title=Representation of confidence associated with a decision by neurons in the parietal cortex|journal=Science|volume=324|issue=5928|pages=759\u2013764|doi=10.1126/science.1169405|pmc=2738936|pmid=19423820}}</ref> Another recent study found that lesions to the ACC in the [[macaque]] resulted in impaired decision-making in the long run of reinforcement guided tasks suggesting that the ACC may be involved in evaluating past reinforcement information and guiding future action.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Kennerley|first1=Steven W.|last2=Walton|first2=Mark E.|last3=Behrens|first3=Timothy E. J.|last4=Buckley|first4=Mark J.|last5=Rushworth|first5=Matthew F. S.|date=July 2006|title=Optimal decision making and the anterior cingulate cortex|journal=[[Nature Neuroscience]]|volume=9|issue=7|pages=940\u2013947|doi=10.1038/nn1724|pmid=16783368}}</ref> A 2012 study found that rats and humans can optimally accumulate incoming sensory evidence, to make statistically optimal decisions.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Brunton|first1=Bingni W.|last2=Botvinick|first2=Matthew M.|last3=Brody|first3=Carlos D.|date=April 2013|title=Rats and humans can optimally accumulate evidence for decision-making|url=http://www.princeton.edu/~matthewb/Publications/Science-2013-Brunton-95-8.pdf|url-status=dead|journal=Science|volume=340|issue=6128|pages=95\u201398|doi=10.1126/science.1233912|pmid=23559254|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160305005810/http://www.princeton.edu/~matthewb/Publications/Science-2013-Brunton-95-8.pdf|archive-date=2016-03-05}}</ref>\n\n=== Emotions ===\n{{Main|Emotions in decision-making}}\n[[Emotion]] appears able to aid the decision-making process. Decision-making often occurs in the face of [[uncertainty]] about whether one's choices will lead to benefit or harm (see also [[Risk]]). The [[somatic marker hypothesis]] is a [[Neurobiology|neurobiological]] theory of how decisions are made in the face of uncertain outcome.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Reimann|first1=Martin|last2=Bechara|first2=Antoine|date=October 2010|title=The somatic marker framework as a neurological theory of decision-making: review, conceptual comparisons, and future neuroeconomics research|journal=[[Journal of Economic Psychology]]|volume=31|issue=5|pages=767\u2013776|doi=10.1016/j.joep.2010.03.002}}</ref> This theory holds that such decisions are aided by emotions, in the form of bodily states, that are elicited during the deliberation of future consequences and that mark different options for behavior as being advantageous or disadvantageous. This process involves an interplay between neural systems that elicit emotional/bodily states and neural systems that map these emotional/bodily states.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Naqvi|first1=Nasir|last2=Shiv|first2=Baba|last3=Bechara|first3=Antoine|date=October 2006|title=The role of emotion in decision making: a cognitive neuroscience perspective|url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/228449030|journal=[[Current Directions in Psychological Science]]|volume=15|issue=5|pages=260\u2013264|citeseerx=10.1.1.137.4677|doi=10.1111/j.1467-8721.2006.00448.x}}</ref> A recent lesion mapping study of 152 patients with focal brain lesions conducted by [[Aron K. Barbey]] and colleagues provided evidence to help discover the neural mechanisms of [[emotional intelligence]].<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Barbey|first1=Aron K.|last2=Colom|first2=Roberto|last3=Grafman|first3=Jordan|date=March 2014|title=Distributed neural system for emotional intelligence revealed by lesion mapping|url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/233916334|journal=Social Cognitive and Affective Neuroscience|volume=9|issue=3|pages=265\u2013272|doi=10.1093/scan/nss124|pmc=3980800|pmid=23171618}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.illinois.edu/news/13/0122emotional_intelligence_AronBarbey.html|title=Researchers map emotional intelligence in the brain|last1=Yates|first1=Diana|website=University of Illinois News Bureau|publisher=[[University of Illinois]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://health.usnews.com/health-news/news/articles/2013/01/28/scientists-complete-1st-map-of-emotional-intelligence-in-the-brain|title=Scientists complete 1st map of 'emotional intelligence' in the brain|author=HealthDay|date=2013-01-28|agency=[[US News and World Report]]}}</ref>\n\n== Decision-making techniques ==\n\nDecision-making techniques can be separated into two broad categories: [[group decision-making]] techniques and individual decision-making techniques. Individual decision-making techniques can also often be applied by a group.\n\n===Group===\n* [[Consensus decision-making]] tries to avoid \"winners\" and \"losers\". Consensus requires that a majority approve a given course of action, but that the minority agree to go along with the course of action. In other words, if the minority opposes the course of action, consensus requires that the course of action be modified to remove objectionable features.\n* [[Voting|Voting-based methods]]:\n** [[Majority]] requires support from more than 50% of the members of the group. Thus, the bar for action is lower than with consensus.\n** [[Plurality voting system|Plurality]], where the largest block in a group decides, even if it falls short of a majority.\n** [[Quadratic voting]] allows participants to cast their ''preference'' and ''intensity of preference'' for each decision (as opposed to a simple ''for'' or ''against'' decision). It addresses issues of [[voting paradox]] and [[Majority rule|majority-rule]].\n** [[Range voting]] lets each member score one or more of the available options. The option with the highest average is chosen. This method has experimentally been shown to produce the lowest [[Bayesian regret]] among common voting methods, even when voters are strategic.{{citation needed|date=December 2011}}\n* [[Delphi method]] is a structured communication technique for groups, originally developed for collaborative forecasting but has also been used for [[Delphi method#Use in policy-making|policy making]].\n* [[Dotmocracy]] is a facilitation method that relies on the use of special forms called Dotmocracy Sheets to allow large groups to collectively brainstorm and recognize agreement on an unlimited number of ideas they have authored.\n* [[Participative decision-making]] occurs when an authority opens up the decision-making process to a group of people for a collaborative effort.\n* [[Decision engineering]] uses a visual map of the decision-making process based on [[system dynamics]] and can be automated through a decision modeling tool, integrating [[big data]], [[machine learning]], and expert knowledge as appropriate.\n\n===Individual===\n* [[Decisional balance sheet]]: listing the advantages and disadvantages (benefits and costs, pros and cons) of each option, as suggested by [[Plato]]'s ''[[Protagoras (dialogue)|Protagoras]]'' and by [[Benjamin Franklin]].<ref>{{cite book |last=Franklin |first=Benjamin |authorlink=Benjamin Franklin |date=1975 |origyear=1772 |chapter=To Joseph Priestley |editor-last=Willcox |editor-first=William Bradford |title=The papers of Benjamin Franklin: January 1 through December 31, 1772 |volume=19 |location=New Haven |publisher=[[Yale University Press]] |pages=299\u2013300 |isbn=978-0300018653 |oclc=310601 |chapterurl=http://franklinpapers.org/yale?vol=19&page=299a |ref=harv}}</ref>\n* [[Expected utility hypothesis|Expected-value optimization]]: choosing the alternative with the highest probability-weighted [[utility]], possibly with some consideration for [[risk aversion]]. This may involve considering the [[opportunity cost]] of different alternatives. See also [[Decision analysis]] and [[Decision theory]].\n* [[Satisficing]]: examining alternatives only until the first acceptable one is found. The opposite is [[Maximization (psychology)|maximizing]] or [[optimizing]], in which many or all alternatives are examined in order to find the best option.\n* [[Argument from authority|Acquiesce to a person in authority]] or an \"expert\"; \"[[Superior orders|just following orders]]\".\n* [[Anti-authoritarianism]]: taking the most opposite action compared to the advice of mistrusted authorities.\n* [[Flipism]] e.g. flipping a coin, cutting a deck of playing cards, and other random or coincidence methods{{spaced ndash}}or prayer, [[tarot]] cards, astrology, [[augurs]], [[revelation]], or other forms of [[divination]], superstition or [[pseudoscience]].\n* [[Automated decision support]]: setting up criteria for automated decisions.\n* [[Decision support system]]s: using [[decision-making software]] when faced with highly complex decisions or when considering many stakeholders, categories, or other factors that affect decisions.\n\n== Steps ==\nA variety of researchers have formulated similar prescriptive steps aimed at improving decision-making.\n\n===GOFER<!--This section is linked from [[Gofer (disambiguation)]] and [[GROW model]] ([[MOS:HEAD]])-->===\nIn the 1980s, psychologist Leon Mann and colleagues developed a decision-making process called GOFER, which they taught to adolescents, as summarized in the book ''Teaching Decision Making To Adolescents''.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Mann |first1=Leon |last2=Harmoni |first2=Ros |last3=Power |first3=Colin |date=1991 |chapter=The GOFER course in decision making |editor1-last=Baron |editor1-first=Jonathan |editor2-last=Brown |editor2-first=Rex V. |title=Teaching decision making to adolescents |location=Hillsdale, NJ |publisher=[[Lawrence Erlbaum Associates]] |pages=61\u201378 |isbn=978-0805804973 |oclc=22507012 |chapterurl=https://books.google.com/books?hl=en&lr=&id=voRVQEAZJYYC&pg=PA61}} See also: {{cite journal |last=Mann |first=Leon |date=July 1989 |title=Becoming a better decision maker |journal=Australian Psychologist |volume=24 |issue=2 |pages=141\u2013155 |doi=10.1080/00050068908259558}}</ref> The process was based on extensive earlier research conducted with psychologist [[Irving Janis]].<ref>{{cite book |last1=Janis |first1=Irving L. |authorlink1=Irving Janis |last2=Mann |first2=Leon |date=1977 |title=Decision making: a psychological analysis of conflict, choice, and commitment |location=New York |publisher=[[Free Press (publisher)|Free Press]] |isbn=978-0029161609 |oclc=2542340 |url=https://archive.org/details/decisionmakingps00janirich }}</ref> GOFER is an [[acronym]] for five decision-making steps:<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Mann |first1=Leon |last2=Harmoni |first2=Ros |last3=Power |first3=Colin |last4=Beswick |first4=Gery |last5=Ormond |first5=Cheryl |date=July 1988 |title=Effectiveness of the GOFER course in decision making for high school students |journal=Journal of Behavioral Decision Making |volume=1 |issue=3 |pages=159\u2013168 |doi=10.1002/bdm.3960010304}}</ref>\n\n# '''G'''oals clarification: Survey values and objectives.\n# '''O'''ptions generation: Consider a wide range of alternative actions.\n# '''F'''acts-finding: Search for information.\n# Consideration of '''E'''ffects: Weigh the positive and negative consequences of the options.\n# '''R'''eview and implementation: Plan how to review the options and implement them.\n\n===DECIDE===\nIn 2008, Kristina Guo published the DECIDE model of decision-making, which has six parts:<ref>{{cite journal |last=Guo |first=Kristina L. |date=June 2008 |title=DECIDE: a decision-making model for more effective decision making by health care managers |journal=The Health Care Manager |volume=27 |issue=2 |pages=118\u2013127 |doi=10.1097/01.HCM.0000285046.27290.90 |pmid=18475113 |ref=harv}}</ref>\n# '''D'''efine the problem\n# '''E'''stablish or '''E'''numerate all the criteria (constraints)\n# '''C'''onsider or '''C'''ollect all the alternatives\n# '''I'''dentify the best alternative\n# '''D'''evelop and implement a [[Action plan|plan of action]]\n# [[Evaluation|'''E'''valuate]] and [[wikt:monitoring|monitor]] the solution and examine [[feedback]] when necessary\n\n===Other===\nIn 2007, Pam Brown of [[Singleton Hospital]] in [[Swansea]], [[Wales]], divided the decision-making process into seven steps:<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.pulsetoday.co.uk/career-coach-decision-making/10967084.article |last=Brown |first=Pam |title=Career coach: decision-making |publisher=Pulse |date=November 29, 2007 |accessdate=July 12, 2012}} {{subscription}}</ref>\n\n# Outline the goal and outcome.\n# Gather data.\n# Develop alternatives (i.e., brainstorming).\n# List pros and cons of each alternative.\n# Make the decision.\n# Immediately take action to implement it.\n# Learn from and reflect on the decision.\n\nIn 2009, professor John Pijanowski described how the Arkansas Program, an ethics curriculum at the [[University of Arkansas]], used eight stages of [[Morality|moral]] decision-making based on the work of [[James Rest]]:<ref>{{cite journal |last=Pijanowski |first=John |date=February 2009 |title=The role of learning theory in building effective college ethics curricula |journal=Journal of College and Character |volume=10 |issue=3 |pages=1\u201313 |doi=10.2202/1940-1639.1088 }}</ref>{{rp|6}}\n# Establishing community: Create and nurture the relationships, norms, and procedures that will influence how problems are understood and communicated. This stage takes place prior to and during a moral dilemma.\n# Perception: Recognize that a problem exists.\n# Interpretation: Identify competing explanations for the problem, and evaluate the drivers behind those interpretations.\n# Judgment: Sift through various possible actions or responses and determine which is more justifiable.\n# Motivation: Examine the competing commitments which may distract from a more moral course of action and then prioritize and commit to moral values over other personal, institutional or social values.\n# Action: Follow through with action that supports the more justified decision.\n# Reflection in action.\n# Reflection on action.\n\n===Group stages===\n\nAccording to B. Aubrey Fisher, there are four stages or phases that should be involved in all group decision-making:<ref>{{cite book |last=Griffin |first=Emory A. |date=1991 |chapter=Interact system model of decision emergence of B. Aubrey Fisher |title=A first look at communication theory |location=New York |publisher=[[McGraw-Hill]] |edition=1st |pages=253\u2013262 |isbn=978-0070227781 |oclc=21973427 |chapterurl=http://www.afirstlook.com/docs/intersys.pdf}}</ref>\n* Orientation. Members meet for the first time and start to get to know each other.\n* Conflict. Once group members become familiar with each other, disputes, little fights and arguments occur. Group members eventually work it out.\n* Emergence. The group begins to clear up vague opinions by talking about them.\n* [[Reinforcement]]. Members finally make a decision and provide justification for it.\n\nIt is said that establishing critical norms in a group improves the quality of decisions, while the majority of opinions (called consensus norms) do not.<ref>{{cite journal |last=Postmes |first=T |title=Quality of decision making and group norms |journal=[[Journal of Personality and Social Psychology]] |year=2001 |volume=80 |issue=6 |pages=918\u2013930 |doi=10.1037/0022-3514.80.6.918 |url=http://psycnet.apa.org/journals/psp/80/6/918/ |last2=Spears |first2=Russell |last3=Cihangir |first3=Sezgin |pmid=11414374}}</ref>\n\nConflicts in socialization are divided in to functional and dysfunctional types. Functional conflicts are mostly the questioning the managers assumptions in their decision making and dysfunctional conflicts are like personal attacks and every action which decrease team effectiveness. Functional conflicts are the better ones to gain higher quality decision making caused by the increased team knowledge and shared understanding.<ref>Brockmann, E., Anthony, W., 2002. Tacit knowledge and strategic decision making. Group & Organization Management. Vol. 27 (4), 436\u2013455. {{doi|10.1177/1059601102238356}}</ref>\n\n== Rational and irrational ==\n\nIn [[economics]], it is thought that if humans are rational and free to make their own decisions, then they would behave according to [[rational choice theory]].<ref name=\"Schacter2011\">{{cite book |last1=Schacter |first1=Daniel L. |authorlink1=Daniel Schacter |last2=Gilbert |first2=Daniel Todd |authorlink2=Daniel Gilbert (psychologist) |last3=Wegner |first3=Daniel M. |authorlink3=Daniel Wegner |date=2011 |origyear=2009 |title=Psychology |url=https://archive.org/details/psychology0000scha |url-access=registration |edition=2nd |location=New York |publisher=Worth Publishers |isbn=9781429237192 |oclc=755079969}}</ref>{{rp|368\u2013370}} Rational choice theory says that a person consistently makes choices that lead to the best situation for himself or herself, taking into account all available considerations including costs and benefits; the rationality of these considerations is from the point of view of the person himself, so a decision is not irrational just because someone else finds it questionable.\n\nIn reality, however, there are some factors that affect decision-making abilities and cause people to make irrational decisions{{spaced ndash}}for example, to make contradictory choices when faced with the same problem [[framing (social sciences)|framed]] in two different ways (see also [[Allais paradox]]).\n\nOne of the most prominent theories of decision making is [[subjective expected utility]] (SEU) theory, which describes the rational behavior of the decision maker.<ref name=\"Crozier\">{{cite book |last1=Crozier |first1=W. Ray |last2=Ranyard |first2=Rob |date=1997 |chapter=Cognitive process models and explanations of decision making |editor1-last=Ranyard |editor1-first=Rob |editor2-last=Crozier |editor2-first=W. Ray |editor3-last=Svenson |editor3-first=Ola |title=Decision making: cognitive models and explanations |series=Frontiers of cognitive science |location=London; New York |publisher=[[Routledge]] |pages=5\u201320 |isbn=978-0415158183 |oclc=37043834}}</ref> The decision maker assesses different alternatives by their utilities and the subjective probability of occurrence.<ref name=\"Crozier\"/>\n\nRational decision-making is often grounded on experience and theories exist that are able to put this approach on solid mathematical grounds so that subjectivity is reduced to a minimum, see e.g. [[scenario optimization]].\n\n== In adolescents vs. adults ==\n{{More citations needed section|date=May 2014}}\n\nDuring their adolescent years, teens are known for their high-risk behaviors and rash decisions. Recent research{{citation needed|date=January 2014}} has shown that there are differences in cognitive processes between adolescents and adults during decision-making. Researchers have concluded that differences in decision-making are not due to a lack of logic or reasoning, but more due to the immaturity of [[psychosocial]] capacities that influence decision-making. Examples of their undeveloped capacities which influence decision-making would be impulse control, emotion regulation, [[delayed gratification]] and resistance to [[peer pressure]]. In the past, researchers have thought that adolescent behavior was simply due to incompetency regarding decision-making. Currently, researchers have concluded that adults and adolescents are both competent decision-makers, not just adults. However, adolescents' competent decision-making skills decrease when psychosocial capacities become present.\n\nRecent research{{citation needed|date=January 2014}} has shown that risk-taking behaviors in adolescents may be the product of interactions between the socioemotional brain network and its [[Executive functions|cognitive-control network]]. The socioemotional part of the brain processes social and emotional stimuli and has been shown to be important in [[Reward system|reward processing]]. The cognitive-control network assists in planning and self-regulation. Both of these sections of the brain change over the course of [[puberty]]. However, the socioemotional network changes quickly and abruptly, while the cognitive-control network changes more gradually. Because of this difference in change, the cognitive-control network, which usually regulates the socioemotional network, struggles to control the socioemotional network when psychosocial capacities are present.{{clarify|date=January 2014}}\n\nWhen adolescents are exposed to social and emotional stimuli, their socioemotional network is activated as well as areas of the brain involved in reward processing. Because teens often gain a sense of reward from risk-taking behaviors, their repetition becomes ever more probable due to the reward experienced. In this, the process mirrors [[addiction]]. Teens can become addicted to risky behavior because they are in a high state of arousal and are rewarded for it not only by their own internal functions but also by their peers around them.\n\nAdults are generally better able to control their risk-taking because their cognitive-control system has matured enough to the point where it can control the socioemotional network, even in the context of high arousal or when psychosocial capacities are present. Also, adults are less likely to find themselves in situations that push them to do risky things. For example, teens are more likely to be around peers who peer pressure them into doing things, while adults are not as exposed to this sort of social setting.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Gardner|first1=Margo|last2=Steinberg|first2=Laurence|authorlink2=Laurence Steinberg|date=July 2005|title=Peer influence on risk taking, risk preference, and risky decision making in adolescence and adulthood: an experimental study|url=http://uwf.edu/smathews/documents/peerroleinrisktakinggardnerandsteinberg.pdf|journal=[[Developmental Psychology (journal)|Developmental Psychology]]|volume=41|issue=4|pages=625\u2013635|citeseerx=10.1.1.556.4973|doi=10.1037/0012-1649.41.4.625|pmid=16060809}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last=Steinberg|first=Laurence|authorlink=Laurence Steinberg|date=April 2007|title=Risk taking in adolescence: new perspectives from brain and behavioral science|journal=[[Current Directions in Psychological Science]]|volume=16|issue=2|pages=55\u201359|citeseerx=10.1.1.519.7099|doi=10.1111/j.1467-8721.2007.00475.x}}</ref>\n\nA recent study suggests that adolescents have difficulties adequately adjusting beliefs in response to bad news (such as reading that smoking poses a greater risk to health than they thought), but do not differ from adults in their ability to alter beliefs in response to good news.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Moutsiana|first1=Christina|last2=Garrett|first2=Neil|last3=Clarke|first3=Richard C.|last4=Lotto|first4=R. Beau|last5=Blakemore|first5=Sarah-Jayne|last6=Sharot|first6=Tali|date=October 2013|title=Human development of the ability to learn from bad news|journal=[[Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences]]|volume=110|issue=41|pages=16396\u201316401|doi=10.1073/pnas.1305631110|pmc=3799330|pmid=24019466}}</ref> This creates biased beliefs, which may lead to greater risk taking.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Reyna|first=Valerie F.|date=November 2013|title=Psychology: Good and bad news on the adolescent brain|journal=[[Nature (journal)|Nature]]|volume=503|issue=7474|pages=48\u201349|doi=10.1038/nature12704|pmid=24172899|ref=harv}}</ref>\n\n== Cognitive and personal biases ==\n\n[[Bias]]es usually affect decision-making processes. They appear more when decision task has time pressure, is done under high stress and/or task is highly complex.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=T|first=Maqsood|last2=A|first2=Finegan|last3=D|first3=Walker|date=2004|title=Biases and heuristics in judgment and decision making: The dark side of tacit knowledge|url=http://researchbank.rmit.edu.au/view/rmit:2008|journal=Issues in Informing Science and Information Technology|language=en|volume=1|issn=1547-5840}}</ref>\n\nHere is a list of commonly debated [[List of biases in judgment and decision-making|biases in judgment and decision-making]]:\n* Selective search for [[evidence]] (also known as [[confirmation bias]]): People tend to be willing to gather facts that support certain conclusions but disregard other facts that support different conclusions. Individuals who are highly defensive in this manner show significantly greater left prefrontal cortex activity as measured by [[Electroencephalography|EEG]] than do less defensive individuals.<ref>{{cite journal |last=Blackhart |first=G. C. |last2=Kline |first2=J. P. |year=2005 |title=Individual differences in anterior EEG asymmetry between high and low defensive individuals during a rumination/distraction task |journal=[[Personality and Individual Differences]] |volume=39 |issue=2 |pages=427\u2013437 |doi=10.1016/j.paid.2005.01.027 |url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/228480310}}</ref>\n* Premature termination of search for evidence: People tend to accept the first alternative that looks like it might work.\n* [[Cognitive inertia]] is the unwillingness to change existing thought patterns in the face of new circumstances.\n* Selective perception: People actively screen out information that they do not think is important (see also [[Prejudice]]). In one demonstration of this effect, discounting of arguments with which one disagrees (by judging them as untrue or irrelevant) was decreased by selective activation of right prefrontal cortex.<ref>{{cite journal |last=Drake |first=R. A. |year=1993 |title=Processing persuasive arguments: 2. Discounting of truth and relevance as a function of agreement and manipulated activation asymmetry |journal=[[Journal of Research in Personality]] |volume=27 |issue=2 |pages=184\u2013196 |doi=10.1006/jrpe.1993.1013}}</ref>\n* [[Wishful thinking]] is a tendency to want to see things in a certain{{spaced ndash}}usually positive{{spaced ndash}}light, which can distort perception and thinking.<ref>{{cite journal |last=Chua |first=E. F. |last2=Rand-Giovannetti |first2=E. |last3=Schacter |first3=D. L. |last4=Albert |first4=M. |last5=Sperling |first5=R. A. |year=2004 |title=Dissociating confidence and accuracy: Functional magnetic resonance imaging shows origins of the subjective memory experience |journal=[[Journal of Cognitive Neuroscience]] |volume=16 |issue=7 |pages=1131\u20131142 |doi=10.1162/0898929041920568 |pmid=15453969 |url=http://dash.harvard.edu/bitstream/handle/1/3627270/Schacter_DissociatingConfidence.pdf}}</ref>\n* [[Choice-supportive bias]] occurs when people distort their memories of chosen and rejected options to make the chosen options seem more attractive.\n* Recency: People tend to place more attention on more recent information and either ignore or forget more distant information (see [[Semantic priming]]). The opposite effect in the first set of data or other information is termed ''[[primacy effect]]''.<ref>{{cite book |last=Plous |first=Scott |date=1993 |title=The psychology of judgment and decision making |location=Philadelphia |publisher=[[Temple University Press]] |isbn=978-0877229131 |oclc=26548229 |ref=harv |url-access=registration |url=https://archive.org/details/thepsyc_plo_1993_00_3134 }}</ref>{{Page needed|date=July 2015}}\n* Repetition bias is a willingness to believe what one has been told most often and by the greatest number of different sources.\n* [[Anchoring and adjustment]]: Decisions are unduly influenced by initial information that shapes our view of subsequent information.\n* [[Groupthink]] is [[peer pressure]] to conform to the opinions held by the group.\n* Source credibility bias is a tendency to reject a person's statement on the basis of a bias against the person, organization, or group to which the person belongs. People preferentially accept statements by others that they like (see also [[Prejudice]]).\n* Incremental decision-making and escalating commitment: People look at a decision as a small step in a process, and this tends to perpetuate a series of similar decisions. This can be contrasted with ''zero-based decision-making'' (see [[Slippery slope]]).\n* [[Attribution theory|Attribution asymmetry]]: People tend to attribute their own success to internal factors, including abilities and talents, but explain their failures in terms of external factors such as bad luck. The reverse bias is shown when people explain others' success or failure.\n* Role fulfillment is a tendency to conform to others' decision-making expectations.\n* Underestimating [[uncertainty]] and the [[illusion of control]]: People tend to underestimate future uncertainty because of a tendency to believe they have more control over events than they really do.\n* [[Framing (social sciences)#Absolute and relative influences|Framing bias]]: This is best avoided by increasing [[numeracy]] and presenting data in several formats (for example, using both absolute and relative scales).<ref name=\"pmid21792695\">{{cite journal |last1=Perneger |first1=Thomas V. |last2=Agoritsas |first2=Thomas |date=December 2011 |title=Doctors and patients' susceptibility to framing bias: a randomized trial |journal=[[Journal of General Internal Medicine]] |volume=26 |issue=12 |pages=1411\u20131417 |doi=10.1007/s11606-011-1810-x |pmid=21792695 |ref=harv |pmc=3235613}}</ref>\n** [[Sunk-cost fallacy]] is a specific type of framing effect that affects decision-making. It involves an individual making a decision about a current situation based on what they have previously invested in the situation.<ref name=\"Schacter2011\"/>{{rp|372}} An example of this would be an individual that is refraining from dropping a class that they are most likely to fail, due to the fact that they feel as though they have done so much work in the course thus far.\n* [[Prospect theory]] involves the idea that when faced with a decision-making event, an individual is more likely to take on a risk when evaluating potential losses, and are more likely to avoid risks when evaluating potential gains. This can influence one's decision-making depending if the situation entails a threat, or opportunity.<ref name=\"Schacter2011\"/>{{rp|373}}\n* [[Optimism bias]] is a tendency to overestimate the likelihood of positive events occurring in the future and underestimate the likelihood of negative life events.<ref>{{cite book |last=Sharot |first=Tali |date=2011 |title=The optimism bias: a tour of the irrationally positive brain |edition=1st |location=New York |publisher=[[Pantheon Books]] |isbn=9780307378484 |oclc=667609433}}</ref> Such biased expectations are generated and maintained in the face of counter-evidence through a tendency to discount undesirable information.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Sharot |first1=Tali |last2=Korn |first2=Christoph W. |last3=Dolan |first3=Raymond J. |date=October 2011 |title=How unrealistic optimism is maintained in the face of reality |journal=[[Nature Neuroscience]] |volume=14 |issue=11 |pages=1475\u20131479 |doi=10.1038/nn.2949 |pmid=21983684 |pmc=3204264}}</ref> An optimism bias can alter risk perception and decision-making in many domains, ranging from finance to health.\n* [[Reference class forecasting]] was developed to eliminate or reduce cognitive biases in decision-making.\n\n== Cognitive limitations in groups ==\n{{Main|Group decision-making#Group discussion pitfalls}}\nIn groups, people generate decisions through active and complex processes. One method consists of three steps: initial preferences are expressed by members; the members of the group then gather and share information concerning those preferences; finally, the members combine their views and make a single choice about how to face the problem. Although these steps are relatively ordinary, judgements are often distorted by cognitive and motivational biases, include \"sins of commission\", \"sins of omission\", and \"sins of imprecision\".<ref name=\"Group Dynamics\">{{cite book|authorlink1=Donelson R. Forsyth |last=Forsyth |first=Donelson R. |date=2014 |origyear=1983 |title=Group dynamics |edition=6th |location=Belmont, CA |publisher=[[Wadsworth Cengage Learning]] |isbn=9781133956532 |oclc=826872491}}</ref>{{Page needed|date=April 2017}}\n\n== Cognitive styles ==\n\n===Optimizing vs. satisficing===\n{{main|Maximization (psychology)}}\n\n[[Herbert A. Simon]] coined the phrase \"[[bounded rationality]]\" to express the idea that human decision-making is limited by available information, available time and the mind's information-processing ability. Further psychological research has identified individual differences between two cognitive styles: ''[[Maximization (psychology)|maximizers]]'' try to make an [[optimal decision]], whereas ''[[satisficer]]s'' simply try to find a solution that is \"good enough\". Maximizers tend to take longer making decisions due to the need to maximize performance across all variables and make tradeoffs carefully; they also tend to more often regret their decisions (perhaps because they are more able than satisficers to recognize that a decision turned out to be sub-optimal).<ref>{{cite book |last=Sparks |first=Erin |date=2007 |chapter=Satisficing |editor1-last=Baumeister |editor1-first=Roy F. |editor1-link=Roy Baumeister |editor2-last=Vohs |editor2-first=Kathleen D. |title=Encyclopedia of social psychology |location=Thousand Oaks, CA |publisher=[[Sage Publications]] |pages=776\u2013778 |isbn=9781412916707 |oclc=123119782 |chapterurl=https://books.google.com/books?id=CQBzAwAAQBAJ&pg=PT926}}</ref>\n\n===Intuitive vs. rational===\n{{Main|Dual process theory}}\n\nThe psychologist [[Daniel Kahneman]], adopting terms originally proposed by the psychologists [[Keith Stanovich]] and Richard West, has theorized that a person's decision-making is the result of an interplay between two kinds of [[cognitive process]]es: an automatic intuitive system (called \"System 1\") and an effortful rational system (called \"System 2\"). System 1 is a bottom-up, fast, and implicit system of decision-making, while system 2 is a top-down, slow, and explicit system of decision-making.<ref>{{cite book |last=Kahneman |first=Daniel |authorlink=Daniel Kahneman |date=2011 |title=Thinking, fast and slow |location=New York |publisher=[[Farrar, Straus, and Giroux]] |isbn=9780374275631 |oclc=706020998}}</ref> System 1 includes simple [[heuristics in judgment and decision-making]] such as the [[affect heuristic]], the [[availability heuristic]], the [[familiarity heuristic]], and the [[representativeness heuristic]].\n\n===Combinatorial vs. positional===\n\nStyles and methods of decision-making were elaborated by [[Aron Katsenelinboigen]], the founder of [[predispositioning theory]]. In his analysis on styles and methods, Katsenelinboigen referred to the game of chess, saying that \"chess does disclose various methods of operation, notably the creation of predisposition-methods which may be applicable to other, more complex systems.\"<ref name=\"Concept of Indeterminism\">{{cite book |last=Katsenelinboigen |first=Aron |authorlink=Aron Katsenelinboigen |date=1997 |title=The concept of indeterminism and its applications: economics, social systems, ethics, artificial intelligence, and aesthetics |location=Westport, CT |publisher=Praeger |isbn=978-0275957889 |oclc=36438766 |url=http://aronkatsenelinboigen.net/CONCEPT_OF_INDETERMINISM.PDF |access-date=2015-07-27 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110723015801/http://aronkatsenelinboigen.net/CONCEPT_OF_INDETERMINISM.PDF |archive-date=2011-07-23 |url-status=dead }}</ref>{{rp|5}}\n\nKatsenelinboigen states that apart from the methods (reactive and selective) and sub-methods (randomization, predispositioning, programming), there are two major styles: positional and combinational. Both styles are utilized in the game of chess. According to Katsenelinboigen, the two styles reflect two basic approaches to [[uncertainty]]: deterministic (combinational style) and indeterministic (positional style). Katsenelinboigen's definition of the two styles are the following.\n\nThe combinational style is characterized by:\n* a very narrow, clearly defined, primarily material goal; and\n* a program that links the initial position with the final outcome.\n\nIn defining the combinational style in chess, Katsenelinboigen wrote: \"The combinational style features a clearly formulated limited objective, namely the capture of material (the main constituent element of a chess position). The objective is implemented via a well-defined, and in some cases, unique sequence of moves aimed at reaching the set goal. As a rule, this sequence leaves no options for the opponent. Finding a combinational objective allows the player to focus all his energies on efficient execution, that is, the player's analysis may be limited to the pieces directly partaking in the combination. This approach is the crux of the combination and the combinational style of play.<ref name=\"Concept of Indeterminism\"/>{{rp|57}}\n\nThe positional style is distinguished by:\n* a positional goal; and\n* a formation of semi-complete linkages between the initial step and final outcome.\n\n\"Unlike the combinational player, the positional player is occupied, first and foremost, with the elaboration of the position that will allow him to develop in the unknown future. In playing the positional style, the player must evaluate relational and material parameters as independent variables. ... The positional style gives the player the opportunity to develop a position until it becomes pregnant with a combination. However, the combination is not the final goal of the positional player{{spaced ndash}}it helps him to achieve the desirable, keeping in mind a predisposition for the future development. The [[pyrrhic victory]] is the best example of one's inability to think positionally.\"<ref>{{cite book |last=Ulea |first=Vera |date=2002 |title=A concept of dramatic genre and the comedy of a new type: chess, literature, and film |location=Carbondale |publisher=[[Southern Illinois University Press]] |isbn=978-0809324521 |oclc=51301095 |pages=[https://books.google.com/books?id=QPWAkw_k5PkC&pg=PA17 17\u201318]}}</ref>\n\nThe positional style serves to:\n* create a predisposition to the future development of the position;\n* induce the environment in a certain way;\n* absorb an unexpected outcome in one's favor; and\n* avoid the negative aspects of unexpected outcomes.\n\n===Influence of Myers-Briggs type===\n\nAccording to [[Isabel Briggs Myers]], a person's decision-making process depends to a significant degree on their cognitive style.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Myers |first1=Isabel Briggs |authorlink1=Isabel Briggs Myers  |last2=Kirby |first2=Linda K. |last3=Myers |first3=Katharine D. |date=1998 |origyear=1976 |title=Introduction to type: a guide to understanding your results on the Myers-Briggs Type Indicator |edition=6th |series=Introduction to type series |location=Palo Alto, CA |publisher=Consulting Psychologists Press |oclc=40336039}}</ref>{{Page needed|date=July 2015}} Myers developed a set of four bi-polar dimensions, called the [[Myers-Briggs Type Indicator]] (MBTI). The terminal points on these dimensions are: ''thinking'' and ''feeling''; ''extroversion'' and ''introversion''; ''judgment'' and ''perception''; and ''sensing'' and ''intuition''. She claimed that a person's decision-making style correlates well with how they score on these four dimensions. For example, someone who scored near the thinking, extroversion, sensing, and judgment ends of the dimensions would tend to have a logical, analytical, objective, critical, and empirical decision-making style. However, some psychologists say that the MBTI lacks reliability and validity and is poorly constructed.<ref>{{cite journal |last=Pittenger |first=David J. |date=2005 |title=Cautionary comments regarding the Myers-Briggs Type Indicator |journal=[[Consulting Psychology Journal: Practice and Research]] |volume=57 |issue=3 |pages=210\u2013221 |doi=10.1037/1065-9293.57.3.210 |url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/232494957}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last=Hogan |first=Robert |authorlink=Robert Hogan (psychologist) |date=2007 |title=Personality and the fate of organizations |location=Mahwah, NJ |publisher=[[Lawrence Erlbaum Associates]] |isbn=978-0805841428 |oclc=65400436 |page=28 |quote=Most personality psychologists regard the MBTI as little more than an elaborate Chinese fortune cookie...}}</ref>\n\nOther studies suggest that these national or [[cross-cultural differences in decision-making]] exist across entire societies. For example, [[Maris Martinsons]] has found that American, Japanese and Chinese business leaders each exhibit a distinctive national style of decision-making.<ref>{{cite journal |last=Martinsons |first=Maris G. |date=December 2006 |title=Comparing the decision styles of American, Chinese and Japanese business leaders |publisher=Best Paper Proceedings of [[Academy of Management]] Meetings, Washington, DC, August 2001 |ssrn=952292 }}</ref>\n\nThe Myers-Briggs typology has been the subject of criticism regarding its poor psychometric properties. <ref>{{Cite journal|last=Pittenger|first=David|date=1993|title=\"Measuring the MBTI ... And Coming Up Short\"|url=http://www.indiana.edu/~jobtalk/HRMWebsite/hrm/articles/develop/mbti.pdf|journal=Journal of Career Planning and Employment.|volume=54 (1)|pages=48\u201352.|via=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Schuwirth|first=Lambert|last2=Cantillon|first2=Peter|date=2004-05-22|title=What the educators are saying|url=http://www.bmj.com/lookup/doi/10.1136/bmj.328.7450.1244|journal=BMJ|language=en|volume=328|issue=7450|pages=1244|doi=10.1136/bmj.328.7450.1244|issn=0959-8138}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Pittenger|first=David J.|date=2005|title=Cautionary comments regarding the Myers-Briggs Type Indicator.|url=http://dx.doi.org/10.1037/1065-9293.57.3.210|journal=Consulting Psychology Journal: Practice and Research|volume=57|issue=3|pages=210\u2013221|doi=10.1037/1065-9293.57.3.210|issn=1939-0149}}</ref>\n\n=== General decision-making style (GDMS) ===\nIn the general decision-making style (GDMS) test developed by Suzanne Scott and Reginald Bruce, there are five decision-making styles: rational, intuitive, dependent, avoidant, and spontaneous.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Scott |first1=Susanne G. |last2=Bruce |first2=Reginald A. |date=1995 |title=Decision-making style: the development and assessment of a new measure |journal=[[Educational and Psychological Measurement]] |volume=55 |issue=5 |pages=818\u2013831 |doi=10.1177/0013164495055005017}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last=Thunholm |first=Peter |date=March 2004 |title=Decision-making style: habit, style or both? |journal=[[Personality and Individual Differences]] |volume=36 |issue=4 |pages=931\u2013944 |doi=10.1016/S0191-8869(03)00162-4}}</ref> These five different decision-making styles change depending on the context and situation, and one style is not necessarily better than any other. In the examples below, the individual is working for a company and is offered a job from a different company.\n* The ''rational'' style is an in-depth search for, and a strong consideration of, other options and/or information prior to making a decision. In this style, the individual would research the new job being offered, review their current job, and look at the pros and cons of taking the new job versus staying with their current company.\n* The ''intuitive'' style is confidence in one's initial feelings and gut reactions. In this style, if the individual initially prefers the new job because they have a feeling that the work environment is better suited for them, then they would decide to take the new job. The individual might not make this decision as soon as the job is offered.\n* The ''dependent'' style is asking for other people's input and instructions on what decision should be made. In this style, the individual could ask friends, family, coworkers, etc., but the individual might not ask all of these people.\n* The ''avoidant'' style is averting the responsibility of making a decision. In this style, the individual would not make a decision. Therefore, the individual would stick with their current job.\n* The ''spontaneous'' style is a need to make a decision as soon as possible rather than waiting to make a decision. In this style, the individual would either reject or accept the job as soon as it is offered.\n\n== Organizational vs. individual level ==\nThere are a few characteristics that differentiate organizational decision-making from individual decision-making as studied in lab experiments <ref>Shapira, Z. (2002). \"Organizational Decision Making. Cambridge Series on Judgment and Decision Making\", Cambridge University Press: pp.4-6. {{ISBN|0521890500}}, 9780521890502 </ref>:\n\n1. Unlike most lab studies of individual decision-making, ''ambiguity'' is pervasive in organizations. There is often only ambiguous information, and there is ambiguity about preferences as well as about interpreting the history of decisions.\n\n2. Decision-making in and by organizations is embedded in a ''longitudinal'' context, meaning that participants in organizational decision-making are a part of ongoing processes. Even if they don't take on active roles in all phases of decision-making, they are part of the Decision Process and its consequences. Decisions in organizations are made in a sequential manner, and commitment may be more important in such processes than judgmental accuracy. In contrast, most lab studies of individual decision-making are conducted in artificial settings (lab) that are not connected to the subjects\u2019 ongoing activities.\n\n3. ''Incentives'' play an important role in organizational decision-making. Incentives, penalties, and their ramifications are real and may have long-lasting effects. These effects are intensified due to the longitudinal nature of decision-making in organizational settings. Incentives and penalties are very salient in organizations, and often they command managerial attention.\n\n4. Many executives, especially in middle management, may make ''repeated decisions'' on similar issues. Managers may develop a sense of using his/her skills (which may be faulty) and a sense of having control and using one's skills are pervasive in managerial thinking about risk taking. Several repeated decisions are made by following rules rather than by using pure information processing modes.\n\n5. ''Conflict'' is pervasive in organizational decision-making. Many times power considerations and agenda setting determine decisions rather than calculations based on the decision's parameters. The nature of authority relations may have a large impact on the way decisions are made in organizations, which are basically political systems.\n\n== See also ==\n{{Portal|Philosophy|Psychology}}\n{{Library resources box |by=no |onlinebooks=no |others=no |about=yes |label=Decision-making}}\n{{div col|colwidth=22em}}\n* [[Aboulomania]]\n* [[Adaptive performance]]\n* [[Agent (economics)]]\n* [[Analytic hierarchy process]]\n* [[Argument map]]\n* [[Business decision mapping]]\n* [[Choice architecture]]\n* [[Choice modelling]]\n* [[Concept driven strategy]]\n* [[Decision downloading]]\n* [[Decision fatigue]]\n* [[Decision quality]]\n* [[Decision-making unit]]\n* [[Foresight (psychology)]]\n* [[Framing (social sciences)]]\n* [[Free will]]\n* [[Idea networking]]\n* [[Robust decision]]\n{{div col end}}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n{{Systems engineering}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Decision-Making}}\n[[Category:Decision-making| ]]\n[[Category:Neuropsychological assessment]]\n[[Category:Unsolved problems in neuroscience]]\n[[Category:Analysis]]\n[[Category:Prediction]]\n", "name_user": "JoRoberts1", "label": "safe", "comment": "To aid in fluidity of article organization", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Decision-making"}
{"title_page": "Wednesday Night Wars", "text_new": "{{short description|Era of professional wrestling}}\nThe '''Wednesday Night Wars''' is the ongoing period of mainstream televised American [[professional wrestling]] that began on October 2, 2019 when [[All Elite Wrestling]] (AEW)'s ''[[AEW Dynamite|Dynamite]]'' debuted on [[TNT (American TV network)|TNT]] opposite [[WWE]]'s ''[[WWE NXT|NXT]]'' on [[USA Network]] in a battle for [[Nielsen ratings|Nielsen Ratings]] each week.<ref name=\"Yahoo\"/><ref name=\"f4wonline\">{{cite web|url=https://www.f4wonline.com/aew-news/aew-dynamite-wins-week-one-wednesday-night-ratings-war-293951|website=f4wonline.com|title=AEW Dynamite wins week one of Wednesday night ratings war|accessdate=2019-10-10}}</ref>\n\nThis is the first direct competition between two major promotions since [[Impact Wrestling]], then known as Total Nonstop Action Wrestling (TNA), briefly moved their flagship series, ''[[Impact! (TV series)|Impact!]]'', [[TNA Impact!'s move to Monday nights|to Monday nights]] opposite ''[[WWE Raw]]'' in 2010, but failed to ever win a single night,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://comicbook.com/wwe/2019/09/26/aew-young-bucks-lessons-learned-tna-failed-combat-wwe/|title=The Young Bucks Explain What Lessons AEW Learned From TNA's Failed Attempt to Combat WWE|website=WWE|language=en|access-date=2019-10-04}}</ref> and over 20 years following the original [[Monday Night Wars]] that lasted from 1995 to 2001.<ref name=\"si\">{{cite web|url=https://www.si.com/wrestling/2019/10/03/aew-nxt-wednesday-night-wars|title=AEW vs. NXT: Wednesday night wrestling wars a throwback to \u201990s - Sports Illustrated|website=si.com|accessdate=2019-10-10}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n\n===Before the war===\nSince the end of the Monday Night Wars, WWE has had a sharp decline in ratings that was caused by the collapse of WCW. One of the main causes for this was the promotion's 2008 shift to a family-friendly approach in which all of its programs received a rating of [[TV Parental Guidelines|TV-PG]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/inside/industrynews/7706710|title=WWE goes PG|date=July 22, 2008|accessdate=September 12, 2016|publisher=[[WWE]]|archivedate=September 1, 2015|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150901161859/http://www.wwe.com/inside/industrynews/7706710}}</ref> In an effort to increase the company's revenue, WWE began to hold many pay-per-views, such as the [[Royal Rumble]] and [[WrestleMania]], inside stadiums that host either [[Major League Baseball|MLB]] or [[National Football League|NFL]] franchises. [[WrestleMania 32]], which was held on April 3, 2016, set records for the highest attendance (at 101,763) and the largest amount of revenue (at $17.3 million) for a professional wrestling event in history.<ref name=WWErecord>{{cite web|title=WWE sets all-time attendance record|url=http://www.wwe.com/shows/wrestlemania/32/article/wwe-sets-all-time-attendance-record|publisher=WWE|date=April 3, 2016|accessdate=April 4, 2016}}</ref> In July of that year, WWE reinstated the [[WWE Brand Extension|brand extension]] after it announced plans to move ''[[WWE SmackDown|SmackDown]]'' to the [[USA Network]] (the broadcaster of ''[[WWE Raw|Raw]]'') and broadcast it live on Tuesday nights; the program had been taped on Tuesday and aired on either Thursday or Friday for its first seventeen years.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2016/tv/news/wwe-smackdown-live-usa-1201782569/|title=WWE's 'Smackdown' Will Move To Live Broadcast On USA (EXCLUSIVE)|last=Steinberg|first=Brian|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|date=May 25, 2016|accessdate=May 25, 2016}}</ref> The [[2016 WWE draft]], which was held on July 19, saw many wrestlers being assigned to ''Raw'' and ''SmackDown'' while accepting wrestlers from ''NXT'' onto either brand.<ref name=\"2016WWEdraft\">{{cite web|title=2016 WWE Draft results: WWE officially ushers in New Era|url=http://www.wwe.com/2016-wwe-draft-results|publisher=WWE|accessdate=July 19, 2016}}</ref> [[WWE Championship|WWE Champion]] [[Dean Ambrose]] (now wrestles as Jon Moxley) was drafted to ''SmackDown'' during the draft and successfully retained the title at [[Battleground (2016)|Battleground]], which resulted in the creation of the [[WWE Universal Championship]] for the ''Raw'' brand.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Caldwell|first1=James|title=7/24 WWE Battleground Results \u2013 Caldwell's Complete Report|url=http://www.pwtorch.com/site/2016/07/24/jcbattlegroundppvreport/|publisher=Pro Wrestling Torch|date=July 24, 2016|accessdate=July 25, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160727004908/http://www.pwtorch.com/site/2016/07/24/jcbattlegroundppvreport/|archive-date=July 27, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> Since that time, WWE had added two other brands: ''[[205 Live]]'' (featuring cruiserweight wrestlers) and ''[[WWE NXT UK|NXT UK]]'' (a United Kingdom-based NXT promotion). \n\nMeanwhile, many other wrestling promotions made numerous attempts to compete with WWE, but most of them suffered a lack of interest. From January to May 2010, TNA decided to program ''[[Impact! (TV series)|Impact!]]'' on Monday nights opposite ''Raw'', but suffered from extremely low ratings in its timeslot due to poor scheduling.<ref name=\"042610a\">{{cite web|url=https://prowrestling.net/article.php?WWE-Raw-vs.-TNA-Impact-ratings-Preliminary-numbers-look-horrible-for-TNA-updated-11504|title=WWE Raw vs. TNA Impact ratings: Preliminary numbers look horrible for TNA (updated)|last=Powell|first=Jason|date=April 27, 2010|accessdate=October 29, 2017|work=Pro Wrestling Dot Net|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171029174105/https://prowrestling.net/article.php?WWE-Raw-vs.-TNA-Impact-ratings-Preliminary-numbers-look-horrible-for-TNA-updated-11504|archivedate=October 29, 2017|df=mdy-all}}</ref> [[Ring of Honor Wrestling]] (ROH) premiered in 2009 on [[HDNet]] to low ratings and was moved to syndication on television stations owned by [[Sinclair Broadcast Group]] in September 2011.<ref name=SinclairTVReturn>{{Cite web|url=http://pwtorch.com/artman2/publish/ROH_News_29/article_51024.shtml|title=ROH News: Full ROH press conference Friday \u2013 start date for new TV show, Internet PPV news & notes (w/Video)|work=Pro Wrestling Torch|date=June 14, 2011|accessdate=2011-06-25|first=James|last=Caldwell}}</ref> \n\nOn June 26, 2018, WWE announced that it would move ''SmackDown'' to [[Fox Broadcasting Company|Fox]] once its existing television deal with the [[USA Network]] expired in late September of the following year.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/fox-wwe-close-five-year-deal-bring-smackdown-network-1123487|title=Fox and WWE Close Five-Year Deal to Bring 'SmackDown' to Network|work=The Hollywood Reporter|date=June 26, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/wrestling-rights-shakeup-fox-nabs-wwe-espn-signs-ufc-nbc-gets-raw-1115156|title=How Fox Bodyslammed Rivals to Win WWE Rights|work=The Hollywood Reporter|date=May 30, 2018}}</ref> Fox had been trying to bolster its sports and reality programming following its acquisition by [[Fox Corporation]], which was expected to become the owner of the network after [[The Walt Disney Company]] [[Acquisition of 21st Century Fox by Disney|announced its acquisition]] of [[21st Century Fox]] in December 2017.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/wrestling-rights-shakeup-fox-nabs-wwe-espn-signs-ufc-nbc-gets-raw-1115156|title=How Fox Bodyslammed Rivals to Win WWE Rights|website=The Hollywood Reporter|language=en|access-date=2019-12-24}}</ref>  \n\nOn January 10, 2018, [[Cody Rhodes|Cody]] and [[The Young Bucks]] (who are members of the stable known as [[The Elite (professional wrestling)|The Elite]]) announced an [[independent circuit|independent]] event known as [[All In (professional wrestling event)|All In]], which was scheduled for September 1 of that year at the [[Sears Centre]] in [[Hoffman Estates, Illinois]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.chicagotribune.com/suburbs/ct-all-in-wrestling-chicago-young-bucks-cody-20180511-story.html |title=7 things to know about 'All In' \u2013 the huge indie wrestling show coming to the Chicago area |first=Brandon|last=Howard|publisher=[[Chicago Tribune]]|date=May 12, 2018|accessdate=January 11, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180514064332/http://www.chicagotribune.com/suburbs/ct-all-in-wrestling-chicago-young-bucks-cody-20180511-story.html|archive-date=May 14, 2018|url-status=live|df=}}</ref> Tickets for the event went on sale on May 13, and sold out in less than an hour.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Johnson |first1=Mike |title=ALL IN.....SOLD OUT? |url=https://www.pwinsider.com/article/117452/all-insold-out.html?p=1 |website=Pwinsider |accessdate=May 14, 2018 |date=May 13, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180515044319/https://www.pwinsider.com/article/117452/all-insold-out.html?p=1 |archive-date=May 15, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> The event was attended by 11,263 people, making it the first event in North America not held by WWE or [[World Championship Wrestling]] (WCW) to sell 10,000 tickets or more since 1993. Four months after All In, Cody and the Young Bucks left Ring of Honor and announced plans to start a new wrestling promotion.<ref>{{cite web|title=ROH Final Battle live results: Jay Lethal vs. Cody|url=https://www.f4wonline.com/roh-results/roh-final-battle-live-results-jay-lethal-vs-cody-272366|first=Justin|last=Knipper|website=F4wonline|publisher=Wrestling Observer Newsletter|accessdate=January 2, 2019|date=December 14, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url =http://www.wrestleview.com/misc-news/57334-1-5-njpw-results-tokyo-japan-bullet-club-turns-on-styles|title = ROH Final Battle Results \u2013 12/14/18 (ROH Title, Triple Threat Ladder War, The Elite says goodbye)|last=Martin|first=Adam|date=December 15, 2018|accessdate=January 9, 2019|work=Wrestleview}}</ref> The promotion, which would become known as [[All Elite Wrestling]] (AEW), began operations on January 1, 2019, and announced that its first event, [[Double or Nothing (2019)|Double or Nothing]], would be held on May 25 of that year.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Currier |first1=Joesph|title=All Elite Wrestling and Double or Nothing officially announced|url=https://www.f4wonline.com/other-wrestling/all-elite-wrestling-and-double-or-nothing-officially-announced-273526|website=F4wonline|publisher=Wrestling Observer Newsletter|date=January 1, 2019|accessdate=January 1, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://uproxx.com/prowrestling/young-bucks-cody-all-elite-wrestling-announcement-2019/|title=The Young Bucks And Cody Officially Announced All Elite Wrestling And Released Some Details|first=Emily|last=Pratt|date=January 1, 2019|publisher=UPROXX|accessdate=January 1, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.foxsportsasia.com/pro-wrestling/all-elite-wrestling/1010194/all-elite-wrestling-news-wwe-tony-khan-to-be-president-of-aew-cody-rhodes-confirms-his-role/|title=All Elite Wrestling officially announced, Cody Rhodes confirms his role|date=January 2, 2019|first=Pratyay|last=Ghosh|publisher=FOX Sports Asia|accessdate=January 2, 2019}}</ref> In the months leading up to the event, AEW signed deals with many wrestlers from WWE and ROH, including [[Adam Page]], [[Chris Jericho]], [[Joey Janela]], Jon Moxley, [[Pac (wrestler)|Pac]], [[Jack Swagger|Jake Hager]], [[Sammy Guevara]], and the tag team [[SoCal Uncensored (professional wrestling)|SoCal Uncensored]] ([[Christopher Daniels]], [[Scorpio Sky]], and [[Frankie Kazarian]]).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.si.com/wrestling/2019/01/10/full-all-elite-wrestling-aew-roster-wrestlers-list|title=Everyone signed to All Elite Wrestling so far|website=SI.com|first=Dan|last=Gartland|date=January 10, 2019|accessdate=February 6, 2019}}</ref>\n\nTen days before Double or Nothing was held, AEW reached a deal with [[WarnerMedia]] to broadcast a weekly show on [[TNT (American TV network)|TNT]], which would later become known as ''[[AEW Dynamite]]''.<ref name=\"CBSTNT\">{{cite web|last1=Silverstein|first1=Adam|title=AEW TV deal: Weekly show to air live on TNT with Turner also streaming pay-per-views |url=https://www.cbssports.com/wwe/news/aew-tv-deal-weekly-show-to-air-live-on-tnt-with-turner-also-streaming-pay-per-views/|website=[[CBS Sports]]|accessdate=May 21, 2019}}</ref> On July 24, 2019, AEW announced that ''Dynamite'' would premiere on Wednesday, October 2 and would be broadcast live every week, marking the return of professional wrestling to WarnerMedia for the first time since TNT broadcast the final episode of WCW's ''[[WCW Monday Nitro|Monday Nitro]]'' on March 26, 2001.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/AEWrestling/status/1154059750264508417|title=#AEW debuts on @TNTDrama - Wednesday, October 2nd LIVE from  Washington DC\u2019s @CapitalOneArena #AreYouElite @AEWonTNTpic.twitter.com/W8vg1CcZrw|last=Wrestling|first=All Elite|date=2019-07-24|website=@AEWrestling|language=en|access-date=2019-10-04}}</ref>\n\nIn August 2019, WWE announced that it was moving ''[[WWE NXT]]'', [[WWE Network]]'s Wednesday night program showcasing its [[NXT (WWE brand)|namesake brand]], to USA Network (marking the show's first broadcast on the network since December 20, 2017) and expanding the program to a live, two-hour broadcast.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.cbssports.com/wwe/news/evolution-of-nxt-continues-triple-h-thrilled-as-wwes-brand-set-for-first-tv-special/|title=Evolution of NXT continues: Triple H thrilled as WWE's brand set for first TV special|work=CBSSports.com|access-date=2017-12-13|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wwenetworknews.com/2019/08/20/nxt-moving-to-usa-network-september-18th-what-does-this-mean-for-wwe-network/|title=NXT Moving to USA Network September 18th; What Does This Mean for WWE Network?|last=Potter|first=Jon|date=2019-08-20|website=WWE Network News|language=en-GB|access-date=2019-08-20}}</ref><ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.si.com/wrestling/2019/08/19/wwe-nxt-usa-network-announcement-aew|title=NXT moving to cable TV on Sept. 18|website=SI.com|language=en|access-date=2019-08-20}}</ref><ref name=\"Variety\" /> Critics felt that the move was an attempt to [[Counterprogramming (television)|counterprogram]] AEW, which was seen as the first major promotion to compete financially with WWE since the closure of WCW in 2001.<ref name=\"CBSTNT\"/>\n\nUnder its new format, ''NXT'' premiered on USA on September 18, two weeks before AEW's broadcast debut on TNT.<ref name=\"Variety\">{{Cite web|url=https://variety.com/2019/tv/news/wwe-nxt-usa-network-deal-1203307413/|title=WWE\u2019s \u2018NXT\u2019 Moves to USA Network as Wrestling Competition Heats Up|last=Littleton|first=Cynthia|last2=Littleton|first2=Cynthia|date=2019-08-20|website=Variety|language=en|access-date=2019-10-04}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://deadspin.com/with-nxt-moving-to-usa-network-wwes-wednesday-night-wa-1837486293|title=With NXT Moving To USA Network, WWE's Wednesday Night War With AEW Is Officially On|website=Deadspin|access-date=2019-10-04}}</ref> Due to scheduling overlap with the final episodes of USA Network series ''[[Suits (American TV series)|Suits]]'', only the first hour of ''NXT'' was scheduled to be broadcast on USA for its first two weeks while the second hour was expected to air on WWE Network.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://comicbook.com/wwe/2019/09/05/wwe-nxt-first-two-live-episodes-usa-network-wwe-network-split-aew/|title=NXT to Split First Two Live Episodes Between USA and WWE Network|website=ComicBook.com|language=en|access-date=2019-09-06}}</ref>\n\n===2019\u20132020: The war begins===\nAt [[AEW All Out|All Out]] on August 31, 2019, AEW announced that three matches would take place to determine the qualifiers for the championship matches that were scheduled to be held during the first month of ''Dynamite''. [[Nyla Rose]] and [[Riho]] won their matches to qualify for the inaugural [[AEW Women's World Championship]] match, while [[The Dark Order]] defeated [[Best Friends (professional wrestling)|Best Friends]] to earn a first-round bye in the tournament for the [[AEW World Tag Team Championship]]. In the main event of the pay-per-view, Chris Jericho defeated Adam Page to become the inaugural [[AEW World Championship|AEW World Champion]].<ref name=\"All Out\">{{cite web|last=Powell|first=Jason|title=AEW All Out results: Powell\u2019s live review of Chris Jericho vs. Hangman Page to become the first AEW Champion, Pentagon Jr. and Fenix vs. The Young Bucks in a ladder match for the AAA Tag Titles, Cody vs. Shawn Spears, Kenny Omega vs. Pac|url=https://prowrestling.net/site/2019/08/31/aew-all-out-results-powells-live-review-of-chris-jericho-vs-hangman-page-to-become-the-first-aew-champion-pentagon-jr-and-fenix-vs-the-young-bucks-in-a-ladder-match-for-the-aaa-tag-titles-cody/|work=Pro Wrestling Dot Net|date=August 31, 2019|accessdate=August 31, 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn the two weeks leading up to the head to head competition, ''NXT'' drew 1.179<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.showbuzzdaily.com/articles/showbuzzdailys-top-150-wednesday-cable-originals-network-finals-9-18-2019.html|title=UPDATED: SHOWBUZZDAILY\u2019s Top 150 Wednesday Cable Originals & Network Finals: 9.18.2019|website=showbuzzdaily.com|access-date=2019-10-04}}</ref> and 1.006<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.showbuzzdaily.com/articles/showbuzzdailys-top-150-wednesday-cable-originals-network-finals-9-25-2019.html|title=UPDATED: SHOWBUZZDAILY\u2019s Top 150 Wednesday Cable Originals & Network Finals: 9.25.2019|website=showbuzzdaily.com|access-date=2019-10-04}}</ref> million viewers respectively. On October 2, 2019, ''Dynamite'' debuted on TNT, which averaged 1.409&nbsp;million viewers.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thewrap.com/all-elite-wrestling-dynamite-ratings-aew-nxt-wwe/|title=TNT's 'All Elite Wrestling: Dynamite' Debut Buries USA Network's 'NXT' in Ratings|date=2019-10-03|website=TheWrap|language=en-US|access-date=2019-10-04}}</ref> ''NXT'' would make their full two-hour debut on USA Network on the same night, which averaged 891,000 viewers.<ref name=\"Yahoo\">{{Cite web|url=https://sports.yahoo.com/premieres-aew-nxt-start-wednesday-110345458.html|title=Premieres of AEW and NXT Start \u2018Wednesday Night Wars\u2019 With a Bang|website=sports.yahoo.com|language=en-US|access-date=2019-10-04}}</ref> The first episode of ''Dynamite'' saw Riho defeat Nyla Rose to win the women's championship and featured a six-man tag team match where Chris Jericho, [[Santana and Ortiz]] (who would comprise [[The Inner Circle (professional wrestling)|The Inner Circle]]) defeat The Elite; the episode of ''NXT'' airing opposite it saw [[The Undisputed Era]] defeat [[Street Profits]] to retain the [[NXT Tag Team Championship]]. ''Dynamite'' would beat ''NXT'' in the ratings among both viewers in the 18\u201349  range and total viewers for its first seven episodes. After the first four weeks, ''NXT'' began to gain ground from ''Dynamite'' when WWE announced that ''NXT'' wrestlers would compete at [[Survivor Series (2019)|Survivor Series]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Satin|first=Ryan|title=NXT Will Be Part of Survivor Series This Year|url=https://www.prowrestlingsheet.com/nxt-survivor-series-involvement/#.Xb4x3dVlDIU|work=Pro Wrestling Sheet|date=October 31, 2019|accessdate=November 2, 2019}}</ref> Competitors from the ''NXT'' brand would go on to win three of the five triple-threat matches at the pay-per-view, which saw [[NXT Women's Championship|NXT Women's Champion]] [[Shayna Baszler]] defeat [[WWE Raw Women's Championship|Raw Women's Champion]] [[Becky Lynch]] and [[WWE SmackDown Women's Championship|SmackDown Women's Champion]] [[Bayley (wrestler)|Bayley]] in the main event.<ref name=\"preSSeries2019\">{{cite web|last=Powell|first=Jason|title=WWE Survivor Series Kickoff Show results: Powell's live review of Lio Rush vs. Kalisto vs. Akira Tozawa for the NXT Cruiserweight Championship|url=https://prowrestling.net/site/2019/11/24/wwe-survivor-series-kickoff-show-results-powells-live-review-of-lio-rush-vs-kalisto-vs-akira-tozawa-for-the-nxt-cruiserweight-championship/|work=Pro Wrestling Dot Net|date=November 24, 2019|accessdate=November 24, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"SSeries2019\">{{cite web|last=Powell|first=Jason|title=WWE Survivor Series results: Powell's live review of Brock Lesnar vs. Rey Mysterio in a No Holds Barred match for the WWE Championship, \"The Fiend\" Bray Wyatt vs. Daniel Bryan for the WWE Universal Championship, Becky Lynch vs. Shayna Baszler vs. Bayley in a non-title match|url=https://prowrestling.net/site/2019/11/24/wwe-survivor-series-results-powells-live-review-of-brock-lesnar-vs-rey-mysterio-in-a-no-holds-barred-match-for-the-wwe-championship-the-fiend-bray-wyatt-vs-daniel-bryan-for-the-wwe-uni/|work=Pro Wrestling Dot Net|date=November 24, 2019|accessdate=November 24, 2019}}</ref> These developments caused ''NXT'' to place first in the ratings for three out of the five remaining weeks of 2019, which culminated in a match where [[Rhea Ripley]] defeated Shayna Baszler to win the women's championship on the December 18 episode of NXT.<ref>{{cite web|last=Moore|first=John|title=11/27 NXT TV results: Moore's live review of Bobby Fish and Kyle O'Reilly vs. Keith Lee and Dominik Dijakovic for the NXT Tag Titles, Lio Rush vs. Akira Tozawa for the NXT Cruiserweight Championship, Survivor Series and WarGames fallout|url=https://prowrestling.net/site/2019/11/27/11-27-nxt-tv-results-moores-live-review-of-bobby-fish-and-kyle-oreilly-vs-keith-lee-and-dominik-dijakovic-for-the-nxt-tag-titles-lio-rush-vs-akira-tozawa-for-the-nxt-cruiserweight-championship/|work=Pro Wrestling Dot Net|date=November 27, 2019|accessdate=November 28, 2019}}</ref> A few weeks earlier, [[Kris Statlander]] began her pursuit of the AEW Women's Championship by securing several victories against other competitors; she would defeat [[Britt Baker]] on the December 18 of ''Dynamite'' to become the number-one contender for the championship.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cbssports.com/wwe/news/aew-dynamite-results-recap-grades-dark-order-makes-presence-felt-chris-jericho-taken-to-the-limit/|title=AEW Dynamite results, recap, grades: Dark Order makes presence felt, Chris Jericho taken to the limit|last=Brookhouse|first=Brent|website=CBS Sports|date=December 18, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.prowrestlingsheet.com/kris-statlander-aew-womens-title-shot/#.XgCltBcza1s|title=Kris Statlander Earns AEW Women's World Title Shot|last=Ashly|first=Kristen|date=December 18, 2019|website=Pro Wrestling Sheet}}</ref> Three weeks later, [[Brandi Rhodes]], [[Awesome Kong]], [[Melanie Cruise|Mel]], and [[Dr. Luther|Luther]] interfered in the championship match between Riho and Statlander; this caused Riho to retain the title.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://pwinsider.com/article/132774/complete-aew-dynamite-tv-report.html?p=1|title=COMPLETE AEW DYNAMITE TV REPORT|last=Strode|first=Cory|website=PWInsider|date=January 8, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn January 1, 2020, ''Dynamite'' regained the ratings lead from ''NXT'' as it was beginning to build up for [[AEW Revolution]]. Jon Moxley, who had defeated [[Kenny Omega]] at [[AEW Full Gear]], had begun his pursuit for the AEW World Championship a few weeks earlier;<ref name=\"Full Gear\">{{cite web|url=https://www.f4wonline.com/aew-results/aew-full-gear-live-results-chris-jericho-vs-cody-296976|title=AEW Full Gear live results: Chris Jericho vs. Cody|publisher=Figure Four Online|website=f4wonline.com|first=Arya|last=Winter|date=November 9, 2019|accessdate=February 28, 2020}}</ref> he would defeat Pac on the show's January 22 episode to become the number-one contender to the title.<ref name=\"Dynamite01222020\">{{cite web|url=https://www.f4wonline.com/aew-results/aew-dynamite-live-results-jericho-cruise-episode-302316|title=AEW Dynamite live results: Jericho Cruise episode|publisher=Figure Four Online|website=f4wonline.com|first=Ethan|last=Renner|date=January 22, 2020|accessdate=February 28, 2020}}</ref> Meanwhile, [[MJF (wrestler)|MJF]] became involved in a rivalry with Cody that began at Full Gear. Cody requested a match against MJF, but he had to agree to three conditions: he could not touch MJF until the match, he would have to face Wardlow in a [[steel cage match]], and he would have to take ten lashes with a leather belt on live TV.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.f4wonline.com/aew-results/aew-dynamite-live-results-texas-street-fight-299271|title=AEW Dynamite live results: Texas street fight|publisher=Figure Four Online|website=f4wonline.com|first=Ethan|last=Renner|date=December 11, 2019|accessdate=February 28, 2020}}</ref> Cody would defeat Wardlow on February 19 to qualify for the match; he would lose his match to MJF ten days later.<ref name=\"Dynamite02192020\">{{cite web|url=https://prowrestling.net/site/2020/02/19/2-19-aew-dynamite-tv-results-barnetts-live-review-of-cody-vs-wardlow-in-a-steel-cage-match-jon-moxley-vs-jeff-cobb-kenny-omega-and-hangman-page-vs-pentagon-jr-and-rey-fenix-for-the-aew-t/|title=2/19 AEW Dynamite TV results: Barnett\u2019s live review of Cody vs. Wardlow in a steel cage match, Jon Moxley vs. Jeff Cobb, Kenny Omega and Hangman Page vs. Pentagon Jr. and Rey Fenix for the AEW Tag Titles, Tag Team battle royal for a tag title shot at AEW Revolution|work=Pro Wrestling Dot Net|first=Jake|last=Barnett|date=February 19, 2020|accessdate=March 1, 2020}}</ref> \n\nAfter [[Charlotte Flair]] won the women's Royal Rumble match at [[Royal Rumble (2020)|Royal Rumble]] on January 26, 2020, she appeared on both ''Raw'' and ''SmackDown'' and did not make an initial decision on her challenger at [[WrestleMania 36]]. Flair held off on making her decision until after Ripley had defended the title at [[NXT TakeOver: Portland]] on February 16.<ref name=\"NXT02052020\">{{cite web|url=https://prowrestling.net/site/2020/02/05/2-5-nxt-tv-results-moores-review-of-charlotte-flair-responding-to-rhea-ripleys-wrestlemania-challenge-ripley-and-bianca-belair-meeting-face-to-face-going-into-their-title-match-at-nxt-takeover/|title=2/5 NXT TV results: Moore\u2019s review of Charlotte Flair responding to Rhea Ripley\u2019s WrestleMania challenge, Ripley and Bianca Belair meeting face to face going into their title match at NXT Takeover: Portland, new NXT Cruiserweight Champion Jordan Devlin\u2019s appearance|date=February 5, 2020|last=Moore|first=John|work=Pro Wrestling Dot Net|accessdate=February 7, 2020}}</ref> At the pay-per-view, Charlotte attacked Rhea and decided to challenge her for the NXT Women's Championship.\n\nAt AEW Revolution on February 29, Moxley defeated Jericho to become the AEW World Champion, while Nyla Rose successfully defended the AEW Women's Championship against Kris Statlander.<ref name=\"Revolution\">{{cite web|url=https://prowrestling.net/site/2020/02/29/aew-revolution-results-powells-live-review-of-chris-jericho-vs-jon-moxley-for-the-aew-championship-kenny-omega-and-hangman-page-vs-the-young-bucks-for-the-aew-tag-titles-cody-vs-mjf-nyla-rose/|title=AEW Revolution results: Powell\u2019s live review of Chris Jericho vs. Jon Moxley for the AEW Championship, Kenny Omega and Hangman Page vs. The Young Bucks for the AEW Tag Titles, Cody vs. MJF, Nyla Rose vs. Kris Statlander for the AEW Women\u2019s Championship, Pac vs. Orange Cassidy|work=Pro Wrestling Dot Net|first=Jason|last=Powell|date=February 29, 2020|accessdate=February 29, 2020}}</ref> On the March 4 episode of ''Dynamite'', Chris Jericho and Sammy Guevara defeated [[Darby Allin]] in a 2-on-1 handicap match after The Inner Circle attacked Moxley, while Pac defeated Chuck Taylor in a singles match and was joined by the [[Lucha Brothers]] in attacking Taylor, [[Trent?|Trent]] and [[Orange Cassidy]] after the match.<ref name=\"Dynamite03042020\">{{cite web|url=https://prowrestling.net/site/2020/03/04/3-4-aew-dynamite-tv-results-powells-live-review-of-jon-moxley-and-darby-allin-vs-chris-jericho-and-sammy-guevara-pac-vs-chuck-taylor-colt-cabana-and-scu-vs-the-dark-order-jake-hager-vs-qt-ma/|title=3/4 AEW Dynamite TV results: Powell\u2019s live review of Jon Moxley and Darby Allin vs. Chris Jericho and Sammy Guevara, Pac vs. Chuck Taylor, Colt Cabana and SCU vs. The Dark Order, Jake Hager vs. QT Marshall, Big Swole vs. Leva Bates|work=Pro Wrestling Dot Net|first=Jason|last=Powell|date=March 4, 2020|accessdate=March 5, 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== March 2020\u2013present: Impact of the coronavirus pandemic ===\nThe fate of what would happen to WWE and AEW programs after the week of March 2 became increasingly grim after the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]] began to impact the United States. After [[Elimination Chamber (2020)|Elimination Chamber]] was held on March 8, several major sporting leagues around the world began to suspend operations in an attempt to keep all players and fans safe and healthy during the course of the pandemic. Both WWE and AEW announced contingency plans to continue operations while the pandemic is in effect. Although WWE had no plans to cancel or postpone WrestleMania 36 (which was relocated to the [[WWE Performance Center]] in [[Orlando, Florida]] on March 16),<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wtsp.com/article/news/health/coronavirus/how-coronavirus-concerns-are-impacting-tampa-bay-events/67-9d960bed-c5dc-4db0-82be-3c04fda72328|title=How coronavirus concerns are impacting Tampa Bay area events|date=March 10, 2020|last=Burch|first=Liz|work=[[WTSP]]|publisher=[[Tegna Inc.]]|accessdate=March 11, 2020}}</ref> a meeting was held by Tampa officials on March 12 to determine the fate of the event; it was decided that WrestleMania 36 would still proceed as planned, barring that the situation does not worsen in a week's time.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/alfredkonuwa/2020/03/12/wwe-wrestlemania-36-to-move-forward-for-now-amid-coronavirus-concerns/#4fabc2496867|title=WWE WrestleMania 36 Will Move Forward For Now Amid Coronavirus Concerns|date=March 12, 2020|last=Konuwa|first=Alfred|work=[[Forbes]]|accessdate=March 12, 2020}}</ref> That same day, WWE announced that future episodes of their television programs (beginning with the March 11 episode of ''NXT'') will be filmed at the WWE Performance Center without an audience until further notice.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://bleacherreport.com/articles/2880809-report-wwe-moves-raw-on-316-day-featuring-stone-cold-to-performance-center|title=Report: WWE Moves Raw on '3:16 Day,' Featuring Stone Cold, to Performance Center|last=Blanchette|first=Rob|date=March 13, 2020|accessdate=March 13, 2020|work=[[Bleacher Report]]}}</ref> Meanwhile, AEW announced that it would relocate future episodes of ''Dynamite'' to [[Daily's Place]] in [[Jacksonville, Florida|Jacksonville]], with only essential personnel being allowed to attend.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cbr.com/aew-dynamite-coronavirus-venue-changes/|title=AEW Announces Venue Changes, Including Blood & Guts Show, Due to COVID-19|date=2020-03-13|website=CBR|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-15}}</ref>\n\nThe first episode of ''NXT'' after the announcement was emanated from the WWE headquarters in [[Stamford, Connecticut]], where hosts [[Triple H]] and [[Tom Phillips (wrestling)|Tom Phillips]] previewed several matches that are set to take place at WrestleMania 36 (one of which was set to involve [[Johnny Gargano]] and [[Tommaso Ciampa]]) and re-aired highlights from matches that were held over the previous few weeks.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ringsidenews.com/2020/03/18/wwe-nxt-results-march-18th-2020/| title=WWE NXT RESULTS \u2013 MARCH 18TH, 2020|last=Dunnells|first=Adam|work=[[Ringside News]]|date=March 18, 2020|accessdate=March 18, 2020}}</ref> Cody opened the corresponding episode of ''Dynamite'' with a short speech explaining the situation; in the main event, The Inner Circle defeated The Elite in a six-man tag team match, after which [[Matt Hardy]] debuted as Nick Jackson's replacement after he was attacked last week.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://bleacherreport.com/articles/2881811-aew-dynamite-results-winners-grades-reaction-and-highlights-from-march-18#slide1|work=[[Bleacher Report]]|date=March 18, 2020|accessdate=March 18, 2020|title=AEW Dynamite Results: Winners, Grades, Reaction and Highlights from March 18|last=Mueller|first=Chris}}</ref>\n\n==Comparison of viewers between ''NXT'' and ''Dynamite''==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable mw-collapsible mw-collapsed\" style=\"font-size: 85%\"\n! Date !! ''NXT''  !! ''Dynamite''\n|- style=\"background:#ddc34f;\"\n| 2019-10-02<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.showbuzzdaily.com/articles/showbuzzdailys-top-150-wednesday-cable-originals-network-finals-10-2-2019.html|title=UPDATED: SHOWBUZZDAILY\u2019s Top 150 Wednesday Cable Originals & Network Finals: 10.2.2019|first=Mitch|last=Metcalf|publisher=Showbuzz Daily|website=showbuzzdaily.com|date=October 3, 2019|accessdate=2019-10-09}}</ref> || 891,000 || 1,409,000\n|- style=\"background:#ddc34f;\"\n| 2019-10-09<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.showbuzzdaily.com/articles/showbuzzdailys-top-150-wednesday-cable-originals-network-finals-10-9-2019.html|title=UPDATED: SHOWBUZZDAILY\u2019s Top 150 Wednesday Cable Originals & Network Finals: 10.9.2019|first=Mitch|last=Metcalf|publisher=Showbuzz Daily|website=showbuzzdaily.com|date=October 10, 2019|accessdate=2019-10-11}}</ref> || 790,000 || 1,140,000\n|- style=\"background:#ddc34f;\"\n| 2019-10-16<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.showbuzzdaily.com/articles/showbuzzdailys-top-150-wednesday-cable-originals-network-finals-10-16-2019.html|title=SHOWBUZZDAILY\u2019s Top 150 Wednesday Cable Originals & Network Finals: 10.16.2019|first=Mitch|last=Metcalf|publisher=Showbuzz Daily|website=showbuzzdaily.com|date=October 17, 2019|accessdate=2019-10-17}}</ref> || 712,000 || 1,014,000\n|-style=\"background:#ddc34f;\"\n| 2019-10-23<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.showbuzzdaily.com/articles/showbuzzdailys-top-150-wednes