=SHOWBUZZDAILY\u2019s Top 150 Wednesday Cable Originals & Network Finals: 4.1.2020|publisher=Showbuzz Daily|website=showbuzzdaily.com|first=Mitch|last=Metcalf|date=April 2, 2020|accessdate=April 2, 2020}}</ref> || 590,000 || 685,000\n|- style=\"background:#FFFF00;\"\n| 2020-04-08<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.showbuzzdaily.com/articles/showbuzzdailys-top-150-wednesday-cable-originals-network-finals-4-8-2020.html|title=SHOWBUZZDAILY\u2019s Top 150 Wednesday Cable Originals & Network Finals: 4.8.2020|first=Mitch|last=Metcalf|publisher=Showbuzz Daily|website=showbuzzdaily.com|date=April 9, 2019|accessdate=2020-04-09}}</ref>|| 693,000 || 692,000\n|-\n| {{legend|#FFFF00|''NXT'' win}}||{{legend|#ddc34f|''Dynamite'' win}}||{{legend|#EE82EE|Tie}}\n|-\n| colspan=\"3\" |{{legend|#00FF7F|Program ran unopposed}}\n|-\n| colspan=\"3\" |'''<u>Overall score</u>'''<br />''Dynamite'': 22<br />''NXT'': 4<br />Tie: 1<br />Ratings unavailable or program not aired: 1\n|}\n\n==See also==\n* [[History of professional wrestling]]\n* [[History of WWE]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{All Elite Wrestling}}\n{{WWE}}\n\n[[Category:2010s in American television]]\n[[Category:All Elite Wrestling]]\n[[Category:History of professional wrestling]]\n[[Category:Mass media rivalries]]\n[[Category:WWE NXT]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Era of professional wrestling}}\nThe '''Wednesday Night Wars''' is the ongoing period of mainstream televised American [[professional wrestling]] that began on October 2, 2019 when [[All Elite Wrestling]] (AEW)'s ''[[AEW Dynamite|Dynamite]]'' debuted on [[TNT (American TV network)|TNT]] opposite [[WWE]]'s ''[[WWE NXT|NXT]]'' on [[USA Network]] in a battle for [[Nielsen ratings|Nielsen Ratings]] each week.<ref name=\"Yahoo\"/><ref name=\"f4wonline\">{{cite web|url=https://www.f4wonline.com/aew-news/aew-dynamite-wins-week-one-wednesday-night-ratings-war-293951|website=f4wonline.com|title=AEW Dynamite wins week one of Wednesday night ratings war|accessdate=2019-10-10}}</ref>\n\nThis is the first direct competition between two major promotions since [[Impact Wrestling]], then known as Total Nonstop Action Wrestling (TNA), briefly moved their flagship series, ''[[Impact! (TV series)|Impact!]]'', [[TNA Impact!'s move to Monday nights|to Monday nights]] opposite ''[[WWE Raw]]'' in 2010, but failed to ever win a single night,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://comicbook.com/wwe/2019/09/26/aew-young-bucks-lessons-learned-tna-failed-combat-wwe/|title=The Young Bucks Explain What Lessons AEW Learned From TNA's Failed Attempt to Combat WWE|website=WWE|language=en|access-date=2019-10-04}}</ref> and over 20 years following the original [[Monday Night Wars]] that lasted from 1995 to 2001.<ref name=\"si\">{{cite web|url=https://www.si.com/wrestling/2019/10/03/aew-nxt-wednesday-night-wars|title=AEW vs. NXT: Wednesday night wrestling wars a throwback to \u201990s - Sports Illustrated|website=si.com|accessdate=2019-10-10}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n\n===Before the war===\nSince the end of the Monday Night Wars, WWE has had a sharp decline in ratings that was caused by the collapse of WCW. One of the main causes for this was the promotion's 2008 shift to a family-friendly approach in which all of its programs received a rating of [[TV Parental Guidelines|TV-PG]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/inside/industrynews/7706710|title=WWE goes PG|date=July 22, 2008|accessdate=September 12, 2016|publisher=[[WWE]]|archivedate=September 1, 2015|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150901161859/http://www.wwe.com/inside/industrynews/7706710}}</ref> In an effort to increase the company's revenue, WWE began to hold many pay-per-views, such as the [[Royal Rumble]] and [[WrestleMania]], inside stadiums that host either [[Major League Baseball|MLB]] or [[National Football League|NFL]] franchises. [[WrestleMania 32]], which was held on April 3, 2016, set records for the highest attendance (at 101,763) and the largest amount of revenue (at $17.3 million) for a professional wrestling event in history.<ref name=WWErecord>{{cite web|title=WWE sets all-time attendance record|url=http://www.wwe.com/shows/wrestlemania/32/article/wwe-sets-all-time-attendance-record|publisher=WWE|date=April 3, 2016|accessdate=April 4, 2016}}</ref> In July of that year, WWE reinstated the [[WWE Brand Extension|brand extension]] after it announced plans to move ''[[WWE SmackDown|SmackDown]]'' to the [[USA Network]] (the broadcaster of ''[[WWE Raw|Raw]]'') and broadcast it live on Tuesday nights; the program had been taped on Tuesday and aired on either Thursday or Friday for its first seventeen years.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2016/tv/news/wwe-smackdown-live-usa-1201782569/|title=WWE's 'Smackdown' Will Move To Live Broadcast On USA (EXCLUSIVE)|last=Steinberg|first=Brian|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|date=May 25, 2016|accessdate=May 25, 2016}}</ref> The [[2016 WWE draft]], which was held on July 19, saw many wrestlers being assigned to ''Raw'' and ''SmackDown'' while accepting wrestlers from ''NXT'' onto either brand.<ref name=\"2016WWEdraft\">{{cite web|title=2016 WWE Draft results: WWE officially ushers in New Era|url=http://www.wwe.com/2016-wwe-draft-results|publisher=WWE|accessdate=July 19, 2016}}</ref> [[WWE Championship|WWE Champion]] [[Dean Ambrose]] (now wrestles as Jon Moxley) was drafted to ''SmackDown'' during the draft and successfully retained the title at [[Battleground (2016)|Battleground]], which resulted in the creation of the [[WWE Universal Championship]] for the ''Raw'' brand.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Caldwell|first1=James|title=7/24 WWE Battleground Results \u2013 Caldwell's Complete Report|url=http://www.pwtorch.com/site/2016/07/24/jcbattlegroundppvreport/|publisher=Pro Wrestling Torch|date=July 24, 2016|accessdate=July 25, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160727004908/http://www.pwtorch.com/site/2016/07/24/jcbattlegroundppvreport/|archive-date=July 27, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> Since that time, WWE had added two other brands: ''[[205 Live]]'' (featuring cruiserweight wrestlers) and ''[[WWE NXT UK|NXT UK]]'' (a United Kingdom-based NXT promotion). \n\nMeanwhile, many other wrestling promotions made numerous attempts to compete with WWE, but most of them suffered a lack of interest. From January to May 2010, TNA decided to program ''[[Impact! (TV series)|Impact!]]'' on Monday nights opposite ''Raw'', but suffered from extremely low ratings in its timeslot due to poor scheduling.<ref name=\"042610a\">{{cite web|url=https://prowrestling.net/article.php?WWE-Raw-vs.-TNA-Impact-ratings-Preliminary-numbers-look-horrible-for-TNA-updated-11504|title=WWE Raw vs. TNA Impact ratings: Preliminary numbers look horrible for TNA (updated)|last=Powell|first=Jason|date=April 27, 2010|accessdate=October 29, 2017|work=Pro Wrestling Dot Net|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171029174105/https://prowrestling.net/article.php?WWE-Raw-vs.-TNA-Impact-ratings-Preliminary-numbers-look-horrible-for-TNA-updated-11504|archivedate=October 29, 2017|df=mdy-all}}</ref> [[Ring of Honor Wrestling]] (ROH) premiered in 2009 on [[HDNet]] to low ratings and was moved to syndication on television stations owned by [[Sinclair Broadcast Group]] in September 2011.<ref name=SinclairTVReturn>{{Cite web|url=http://pwtorch.com/artman2/publish/ROH_News_29/article_51024.shtml|title=ROH News: Full ROH press conference Friday \u2013 start date for new TV show, Internet PPV news & notes (w/Video)|work=Pro Wrestling Torch|date=June 14, 2011|accessdate=2011-06-25|first=James|last=Caldwell}}</ref> \n\nOn June 26, 2018, WWE announced that it would move ''SmackDown'' to [[Fox Broadcasting Company|Fox]] once its existing television deal with the [[USA Network]] expired in late September of the following year.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/fox-wwe-close-five-year-deal-bring-smackdown-network-1123487|title=Fox and WWE Close Five-Year Deal to Bring 'SmackDown' to Network|work=The Hollywood Reporter|date=June 26, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/wrestling-rights-shakeup-fox-nabs-wwe-espn-signs-ufc-nbc-gets-raw-1115156|title=How Fox Bodyslammed Rivals to Win WWE Rights|work=The Hollywood Reporter|date=May 30, 2018}}</ref> Fox had been trying to bolster its sports and reality programming following its acquisition by [[Fox Corporation]], which was expected to become the owner of the network after [[The Walt Disney Company]] [[Acquisition of 21st Century Fox by Disney|announced its acquisition]] of [[21st Century Fox]] in December 2017.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/wrestling-rights-shakeup-fox-nabs-wwe-espn-signs-ufc-nbc-gets-raw-1115156|title=How Fox Bodyslammed Rivals to Win WWE Rights|website=The Hollywood Reporter|language=en|access-date=2019-12-24}}</ref>  \n\nOn January 10, 2018, [[Cody Rhodes|Cody]] and [[The Young Bucks]] (who are members of the stable known as [[The Elite (professional wrestling)|The Elite]]) announced an [[independent circuit|independent]] event known as [[All In (professional wrestling event)|All In]], which was scheduled for September 1 of that year at the [[Sears Centre]] in [[Hoffman Estates, Illinois]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.chicagotribune.com/suburbs/ct-all-in-wrestling-chicago-young-bucks-cody-20180511-story.html |title=7 things to know about 'All In' \u2013 the huge indie wrestling show coming to the Chicago area |first=Brandon|last=Howard|publisher=[[Chicago Tribune]]|date=May 12, 2018|accessdate=January 11, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180514064332/http://www.chicagotribune.com/suburbs/ct-all-in-wrestling-chicago-young-bucks-cody-20180511-story.html|archive-date=May 14, 2018|url-status=live|df=}}</ref> Tickets for the event went on sale on May 13, and sold out in less than an hour.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Johnson |first1=Mike |title=ALL IN.....SOLD OUT? |url=https://www.pwinsider.com/article/117452/all-insold-out.html?p=1 |website=Pwinsider |accessdate=May 14, 2018 |date=May 13, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180515044319/https://www.pwinsider.com/article/117452/all-insold-out.html?p=1 |archive-date=May 15, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> The event was attended by 11,263 people, making it the first event in North America not held by WWE or [[World Championship Wrestling]] (WCW) to sell 10,000 tickets or more since 1993. Four months after All In, Cody and the Young Bucks left Ring of Honor and announced plans to start a new wrestling promotion.<ref>{{cite web|title=ROH Final Battle live results: Jay Lethal vs. Cody|url=https://www.f4wonline.com/roh-results/roh-final-battle-live-results-jay-lethal-vs-cody-272366|first=Justin|last=Knipper|website=F4wonline|publisher=Wrestling Observer Newsletter|accessdate=January 2, 2019|date=December 14, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url =http://www.wrestleview.com/misc-news/57334-1-5-njpw-results-tokyo-japan-bullet-club-turns-on-styles|title = ROH Final Battle Results \u2013 12/14/18 (ROH Title, Triple Threat Ladder War, The Elite says goodbye)|last=Martin|first=Adam|date=December 15, 2018|accessdate=January 9, 2019|work=Wrestleview}}</ref> The promotion, which would become known as [[All Elite Wrestling]] (AEW), began operations on January 1, 2019, and announced that its first event, [[Double or Nothing (2019)|Double or Nothing]], would be held on May 25 of that year.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Currier |first1=Joesph|title=All Elite Wrestling and Double or Nothing officially announced|url=https://www.f4wonline.com/other-wrestling/all-elite-wrestling-and-double-or-nothing-officially-announced-273526|website=F4wonline|publisher=Wrestling Observer Newsletter|date=January 1, 2019|accessdate=January 1, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://uproxx.com/prowrestling/young-bucks-cody-all-elite-wrestling-announcement-2019/|title=The Young Bucks And Cody Officially Announced All Elite Wrestling And Released Some Details|first=Emily|last=Pratt|date=January 1, 2019|publisher=UPROXX|accessdate=January 1, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.foxsportsasia.com/pro-wrestling/all-elite-wrestling/1010194/all-elite-wrestling-news-wwe-tony-khan-to-be-president-of-aew-cody-rhodes-confirms-his-role/|title=All Elite Wrestling officially announced, Cody Rhodes confirms his role|date=January 2, 2019|first=Pratyay|last=Ghosh|publisher=FOX Sports Asia|accessdate=January 2, 2019}}</ref> In the months leading up to the event, AEW signed deals with many wrestlers from WWE and ROH, including [[Adam Page]], [[Chris Jericho]], [[Joey Janela]], Jon Moxley, [[Pac (wrestler)|Pac]], [[Jack Swagger|Jake Hager]], [[Sammy Guevara]], and the tag team [[SoCal Uncensored (professional wrestling)|SoCal Uncensored]] ([[Christopher Daniels]], [[Scorpio Sky]], and [[Frankie Kazarian]]).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.si.com/wrestling/2019/01/10/full-all-elite-wrestling-aew-roster-wrestlers-list|title=Everyone signed to All Elite Wrestling so far|website=SI.com|first=Dan|last=Gartland|date=January 10, 2019|accessdate=February 6, 2019}}</ref>\n\nTen days before Double or Nothing was held, AEW reached a deal with [[WarnerMedia]] to broadcast a weekly show on [[TNT (American TV network)|TNT]], which would later become known as ''[[AEW Dynamite]]''.<ref name=\"CBSTNT\">{{cite web|last1=Silverstein|first1=Adam|title=AEW TV deal: Weekly show to air live on TNT with Turner also streaming pay-per-views |url=https://www.cbssports.com/wwe/news/aew-tv-deal-weekly-show-to-air-live-on-tnt-with-turner-also-streaming-pay-per-views/|website=[[CBS Sports]]|accessdate=May 21, 2019}}</ref> On July 24, 2019, AEW announced that ''Dynamite'' would premiere on Wednesday, October 2 and would be broadcast live every week, marking the return of professional wrestling to WarnerMedia for the first time since TNT broadcast the final episode of WCW's ''[[WCW Monday Nitro|Monday Nitro]]'' on March 26, 2001.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/AEWrestling/status/1154059750264508417|title=#AEW debuts on @TNTDrama - Wednesday, October 2nd LIVE from  Washington DC\u2019s @CapitalOneArena #AreYouElite @AEWonTNTpic.twitter.com/W8vg1CcZrw|last=Wrestling|first=All Elite|date=2019-07-24|website=@AEWrestling|language=en|access-date=2019-10-04}}</ref>\n\nIn August 2019, WWE announced that it was moving ''[[WWE NXT]]'', [[WWE Network]]'s Wednesday night program showcasing its [[NXT (WWE brand)|namesake brand]], to USA Network (marking the show's first broadcast on the network since December 20, 2017) and expanding the program to a live, two-hour broadcast.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.cbssports.com/wwe/news/evolution-of-nxt-continues-triple-h-thrilled-as-wwes-brand-set-for-first-tv-special/|title=Evolution of NXT continues: Triple H thrilled as WWE's brand set for first TV special|work=CBSSports.com|access-date=2017-12-13|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wwenetworknews.com/2019/08/20/nxt-moving-to-usa-network-september-18th-what-does-this-mean-for-wwe-network/|title=NXT Moving to USA Network September 18th; What Does This Mean for WWE Network?|last=Potter|first=Jon|date=2019-08-20|website=WWE Network News|language=en-GB|access-date=2019-08-20}}</ref><ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.si.com/wrestling/2019/08/19/wwe-nxt-usa-network-announcement-aew|title=NXT moving to cable TV on Sept. 18|website=SI.com|language=en|access-date=2019-08-20}}</ref><ref name=\"Variety\" /> Critics felt that the move was an attempt to [[Counterprogramming (television)|counterprogram]] AEW, which was seen as the first major promotion to compete financially with WWE since the closure of WCW in 2001.<ref name=\"CBSTNT\"/>\n\nUnder its new format, ''NXT'' premiered on USA on September 18, two weeks before AEW's broadcast debut on TNT.<ref name=\"Variety\">{{Cite web|url=https://variety.com/2019/tv/news/wwe-nxt-usa-network-deal-1203307413/|title=WWE\u2019s \u2018NXT\u2019 Moves to USA Network as Wrestling Competition Heats Up|last=Littleton|first=Cynthia|last2=Littleton|first2=Cynthia|date=2019-08-20|website=Variety|language=en|access-date=2019-10-04}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://deadspin.com/with-nxt-moving-to-usa-network-wwes-wednesday-night-wa-1837486293|title=With NXT Moving To USA Network, WWE's Wednesday Night War With AEW Is Officially On|website=Deadspin|access-date=2019-10-04}}</ref> Due to scheduling overlap with the final episodes of USA Network series ''[[Suits (American TV series)|Suits]]'', only the first hour of ''NXT'' was scheduled to be broadcast on USA for its first two weeks while the second hour was expected to air on WWE Network.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://comicbook.com/wwe/2019/09/05/wwe-nxt-first-two-live-episodes-usa-network-wwe-network-split-aew/|title=NXT to Split First Two Live Episodes Between USA and WWE Network|website=ComicBook.com|language=en|access-date=2019-09-06}}</ref>\n\n===2019\u20132020: The war begins===\nAt [[AEW All Out|All Out]] on August 31, 2019, AEW announced that three matches would take place to determine the qualifiers for the championship matches that were scheduled to be held during the first month of ''Dynamite''. [[Nyla Rose]] and [[Riho]] won their matches to qualify for the inaugural [[AEW Women's World Championship]] match, while [[The Dark Order]] defeated [[Best Friends (professional wrestling)|Best Friends]] to earn a first-round bye in the tournament for the [[AEW World Tag Team Championship]]. In the main event of the pay-per-view, Chris Jericho defeated Adam Page to become the inaugural [[AEW World Championship|AEW World Champion]].<ref name=\"All Out\">{{cite web|last=Powell|first=Jason|title=AEW All Out results: Powell\u2019s live review of Chris Jericho vs. Hangman Page to become the first AEW Champion, Pentagon Jr. and Fenix vs. The Young Bucks in a ladder match for the AAA Tag Titles, Cody vs. Shawn Spears, Kenny Omega vs. Pac|url=https://prowrestling.net/site/2019/08/31/aew-all-out-results-powells-live-review-of-chris-jericho-vs-hangman-page-to-become-the-first-aew-champion-pentagon-jr-and-fenix-vs-the-young-bucks-in-a-ladder-match-for-the-aaa-tag-titles-cody/|work=Pro Wrestling Dot Net|date=August 31, 2019|accessdate=August 31, 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn the two weeks leading up to the head to head competition, ''NXT'' drew 1.179<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.showbuzzdaily.com/articles/showbuzzdailys-top-150-wednesday-cable-originals-network-finals-9-18-2019.html|title=UPDATED: SHOWBUZZDAILY\u2019s Top 150 Wednesday Cable Originals & Network Finals: 9.18.2019|website=showbuzzdaily.com|access-date=2019-10-04}}</ref> and 1.006<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.showbuzzdaily.com/articles/showbuzzdailys-top-150-wednesday-cable-originals-network-finals-9-25-2019.html|title=UPDATED: SHOWBUZZDAILY\u2019s Top 150 Wednesday Cable Originals & Network Finals: 9.25.2019|website=showbuzzdaily.com|access-date=2019-10-04}}</ref> million viewers respectively. On October 2, 2019, ''Dynamite'' debuted on TNT, which averaged 1.409&nbsp;million viewers.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thewrap.com/all-elite-wrestling-dynamite-ratings-aew-nxt-wwe/|title=TNT's 'All Elite Wrestling: Dynamite' Debut Buries USA Network's 'NXT' in Ratings|date=2019-10-03|website=TheWrap|language=en-US|access-date=2019-10-04}}</ref> ''NXT'' would make their full two-hour debut on USA Network on the same night, which averaged 891,000 viewers.<ref name=\"Yahoo\">{{Cite web|url=https://sports.yahoo.com/premieres-aew-nxt-start-wednesday-110345458.html|title=Premieres of AEW and NXT Start \u2018Wednesday Night Wars\u2019 With a Bang|website=sports.yahoo.com|language=en-US|access-date=2019-10-04}}</ref> The first episode of ''Dynamite'' saw Riho defeat Nyla Rose to win the women's championship and featured a six-man tag team match where Chris Jericho, [[Santana and Ortiz]] (who would comprise [[The Inner Circle (professional wrestling)|The Inner Circle]]) defeat The Elite; the episode of ''NXT'' airing opposite it saw [[The Undisputed Era]] defeat [[Street Profits]] to retain the [[NXT Tag Team Championship]]. ''Dynamite'' would beat ''NXT'' in the ratings among both viewers in the 18\u201349  range and total viewers for its first seven episodes. After the first four weeks, ''NXT'' began to gain ground from ''Dynamite'' when WWE announced that ''NXT'' wrestlers would compete at [[Survivor Series (2019)|Survivor Series]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Satin|first=Ryan|title=NXT Will Be Part of Survivor Series This Year|url=https://www.prowrestlingsheet.com/nxt-survivor-series-involvement/#.Xb4x3dVlDIU|work=Pro Wrestling Sheet|date=October 31, 2019|accessdate=November 2, 2019}}</ref> Competitors from the ''NXT'' brand would go on to win three of the five triple-threat matches at the pay-per-view, which saw [[NXT Women's Championship|NXT Women's Champion]] [[Shayna Baszler]] defeat [[WWE Raw Women's Championship|Raw Women's Champion]] [[Becky Lynch]] and [[WWE SmackDown Women's Championship|SmackDown Women's Champion]] [[Bayley (wrestler)|Bayley]] in the main event.<ref name=\"preSSeries2019\">{{cite web|last=Powell|first=Jason|title=WWE Survivor Series Kickoff Show results: Powell's live review of Lio Rush vs. Kalisto vs. Akira Tozawa for the NXT Cruiserweight Championship|url=https://prowrestling.net/site/2019/11/24/wwe-survivor-series-kickoff-show-results-powells-live-review-of-lio-rush-vs-kalisto-vs-akira-tozawa-for-the-nxt-cruiserweight-championship/|work=Pro Wrestling Dot Net|date=November 24, 2019|accessdate=November 24, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"SSeries2019\">{{cite web|last=Powell|first=Jason|title=WWE Survivor Series results: Powell's live review of Brock Lesnar vs. Rey Mysterio in a No Holds Barred match for the WWE Championship, \"The Fiend\" Bray Wyatt vs. Daniel Bryan for the WWE Universal Championship, Becky Lynch vs. Shayna Baszler vs. Bayley in a non-title match|url=https://prowrestling.net/site/2019/11/24/wwe-survivor-series-results-powells-live-review-of-brock-lesnar-vs-rey-mysterio-in-a-no-holds-barred-match-for-the-wwe-championship-the-fiend-bray-wyatt-vs-daniel-bryan-for-the-wwe-uni/|work=Pro Wrestling Dot Net|date=November 24, 2019|accessdate=November 24, 2019}}</ref> These developments caused ''NXT'' to place first in the ratings for three out of the five remaining weeks of 2019, which culminated in a match where [[Rhea Ripley]] defeated Shayna Baszler to win the women's championship on the December 18 episode of NXT.<ref>{{cite web|last=Moore|first=John|title=11/27 NXT TV results: Moore's live review of Bobby Fish and Kyle O'Reilly vs. Keith Lee and Dominik Dijakovic for the NXT Tag Titles, Lio Rush vs. Akira Tozawa for the NXT Cruiserweight Championship, Survivor Series and WarGames fallout|url=https://prowrestling.net/site/2019/11/27/11-27-nxt-tv-results-moores-live-review-of-bobby-fish-and-kyle-oreilly-vs-keith-lee-and-dominik-dijakovic-for-the-nxt-tag-titles-lio-rush-vs-akira-tozawa-for-the-nxt-cruiserweight-championship/|work=Pro Wrestling Dot Net|date=November 27, 2019|accessdate=November 28, 2019}}</ref> A few weeks earlier, [[Kris Statlander]] began her pursuit of the AEW Women's Championship by securing several victories against other competitors; she would defeat [[Britt Baker]] on the December 18 of ''Dynamite'' to become the number-one contender for the championship.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cbssports.com/wwe/news/aew-dynamite-results-recap-grades-dark-order-makes-presence-felt-chris-jericho-taken-to-the-limit/|title=AEW Dynamite results, recap, grades: Dark Order makes presence felt, Chris Jericho taken to the limit|last=Brookhouse|first=Brent|website=CBS Sports|date=December 18, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.prowrestlingsheet.com/kris-statlander-aew-womens-title-shot/#.XgCltBcza1s|title=Kris Statlander Earns AEW Women's World Title Shot|last=Ashly|first=Kristen|date=December 18, 2019|website=Pro Wrestling Sheet}}</ref> Three weeks later, [[Brandi Rhodes]], [[Awesome Kong]], [[Melanie Cruise|Mel]], and [[Dr. Luther|Luther]] interfered in the championship match between Riho and Statlander; this caused Riho to retain the title.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://pwinsider.com/article/132774/complete-aew-dynamite-tv-report.html?p=1|title=COMPLETE AEW DYNAMITE TV REPORT|last=Strode|first=Cory|website=PWInsider|date=January 8, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn January 1, 2020, ''Dynamite'' regained the ratings lead from ''NXT'' as it was beginning to build up for [[AEW Revolution]]. Jon Moxley, who had defeated [[Kenny Omega]] at [[AEW Full Gear]], had begun his pursuit for the AEW World Championship a few weeks earlier;<ref name=\"Full Gear\">{{cite web|url=https://www.f4wonline.com/aew-results/aew-full-gear-live-results-chris-jericho-vs-cody-296976|title=AEW Full Gear live results: Chris Jericho vs. Cody|publisher=Figure Four Online|website=f4wonline.com|first=Arya|last=Winter|date=November 9, 2019|accessdate=February 28, 2020}}</ref> he would defeat Pac on the show's January 22 episode to become the number-one contender to the title.<ref name=\"Dynamite01222020\">{{cite web|url=https://www.f4wonline.com/aew-results/aew-dynamite-live-results-jericho-cruise-episode-302316|title=AEW Dynamite live results: Jericho Cruise episode|publisher=Figure Four Online|website=f4wonline.com|first=Ethan|last=Renner|date=January 22, 2020|accessdate=February 28, 2020}}</ref> Meanwhile, [[MJF (wrestler)|MJF]] became involved in a rivalry with Cody that began at Full Gear. Cody requested a match against MJF, but he had to agree to three conditions: he could not touch MJF until the match, he would have to face Wardlow in a [[steel cage match]], and he would have to take ten lashes with a leather belt on live TV.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.f4wonline.com/aew-results/aew-dynamite-live-results-texas-street-fight-299271|title=AEW Dynamite live results: Texas street fight|publisher=Figure Four Online|website=f4wonline.com|first=Ethan|last=Renner|date=December 11, 2019|accessdate=February 28, 2020}}</ref> Cody would defeat Wardlow on February 19 to qualify for the match; he would lose his match to MJF ten days later.<ref name=\"Dynamite02192020\">{{cite web|url=https://prowrestling.net/site/2020/02/19/2-19-aew-dynamite-tv-results-barnetts-live-review-of-cody-vs-wardlow-in-a-steel-cage-match-jon-moxley-vs-jeff-cobb-kenny-omega-and-hangman-page-vs-pentagon-jr-and-rey-fenix-for-the-aew-t/|title=2/19 AEW Dynamite TV results: Barnett\u2019s live review of Cody vs. Wardlow in a steel cage match, Jon Moxley vs. Jeff Cobb, Kenny Omega and Hangman Page vs. Pentagon Jr. and Rey Fenix for the AEW Tag Titles, Tag Team battle royal for a tag title shot at AEW Revolution|work=Pro Wrestling Dot Net|first=Jake|last=Barnett|date=February 19, 2020|accessdate=March 1, 2020}}</ref> \n\nAfter [[Charlotte Flair]] won the women's Royal Rumble match at [[Royal Rumble (2020)|Royal Rumble]] on January 26, 2020, she appeared on both ''Raw'' and ''SmackDown'' and did not make an initial decision on her challenger at [[WrestleMania 36]]. Flair held off on making her decision until after Ripley had defended the title at [[NXT TakeOver: Portland]] on February 16.<ref name=\"NXT02052020\">{{cite web|url=https://prowrestling.net/site/2020/02/05/2-5-nxt-tv-results-moores-review-of-charlotte-flair-responding-to-rhea-ripleys-wrestlemania-challenge-ripley-and-bianca-belair-meeting-face-to-face-going-into-their-title-match-at-nxt-takeover/|title=2/5 NXT TV results: Moore\u2019s review of Charlotte Flair responding to Rhea Ripley\u2019s WrestleMania challenge, Ripley and Bianca Belair meeting face to face going into their title match at NXT Takeover: Portland, new NXT Cruiserweight Champion Jordan Devlin\u2019s appearance|date=February 5, 2020|last=Moore|first=John|work=Pro Wrestling Dot Net|accessdate=February 7, 2020}}</ref> At the pay-per-view, Charlotte attacked Rhea and decided to challenge her for the NXT Women's Championship.\n\nAt AEW Revolution on February 29, Moxley defeated Jericho to become the AEW World Champion, while Nyla Rose successfully defended the AEW Women's Championship against Kris Statlander.<ref name=\"Revolution\">{{cite web|url=https://prowrestling.net/site/2020/02/29/aew-revolution-results-powells-live-review-of-chris-jericho-vs-jon-moxley-for-the-aew-championship-kenny-omega-and-hangman-page-vs-the-young-bucks-for-the-aew-tag-titles-cody-vs-mjf-nyla-rose/|title=AEW Revolution results: Powell\u2019s live review of Chris Jericho vs. Jon Moxley for the AEW Championship, Kenny Omega and Hangman Page vs. The Young Bucks for the AEW Tag Titles, Cody vs. MJF, Nyla Rose vs. Kris Statlander for the AEW Women\u2019s Championship, Pac vs. Orange Cassidy|work=Pro Wrestling Dot Net|first=Jason|last=Powell|date=February 29, 2020|accessdate=February 29, 2020}}</ref> On the March 4 episode of ''Dynamite'', Chris Jericho and Sammy Guevara defeated [[Darby Allin]] in a 2-on-1 handicap match after The Inner Circle attacked Moxley, while Pac defeated Chuck Taylor in a singles match and was joined by the [[Lucha Brothers]] in attacking Taylor, [[Trent?|Trent]] and [[Orange Cassidy]] after the match.<ref name=\"Dynamite03042020\">{{cite web|url=https://prowrestling.net/site/2020/03/04/3-4-aew-dynamite-tv-results-powells-live-review-of-jon-moxley-and-darby-allin-vs-chris-jericho-and-sammy-guevara-pac-vs-chuck-taylor-colt-cabana-and-scu-vs-the-dark-order-jake-hager-vs-qt-ma/|title=3/4 AEW Dynamite TV results: Powell\u2019s live review of Jon Moxley and Darby Allin vs. Chris Jericho and Sammy Guevara, Pac vs. Chuck Taylor, Colt Cabana and SCU vs. The Dark Order, Jake Hager vs. QT Marshall, Big Swole vs. Leva Bates|work=Pro Wrestling Dot Net|first=Jason|last=Powell|date=March 4, 2020|accessdate=March 5, 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== March 2020\u2013present: Impact of the coronavirus pandemic ===\nThe fate of what would happen to WWE and AEW programs after the week of March 2 became increasingly grim after the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]] began to impact the United States. After [[Elimination Chamber (2020)|Elimination Chamber]] was held on March 8, several major sporting leagues around the world began to suspend operations in an attempt to keep all players and fans safe and healthy during the course of the pandemic. Both WWE and AEW announced contingency plans to continue operations while the pandemic is in effect. Although WWE had no plans to cancel or postpone WrestleMania 36 (which was relocated to the [[WWE Performance Center]] in [[Orlando, Florida]] on March 16),<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wtsp.com/article/news/health/coronavirus/how-coronavirus-concerns-are-impacting-tampa-bay-events/67-9d960bed-c5dc-4db0-82be-3c04fda72328|title=How coronavirus concerns are impacting Tampa Bay area events|date=March 10, 2020|last=Burch|first=Liz|work=[[WTSP]]|publisher=[[Tegna Inc.]]|accessdate=March 11, 2020}}</ref> a meeting was held by Tampa officials on March 12 to determine the fate of the event; it was decided that WrestleMania 36 would still proceed as planned, barring that the situation does not worsen in a week's time.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/alfredkonuwa/2020/03/12/wwe-wrestlemania-36-to-move-forward-for-now-amid-coronavirus-concerns/#4fabc2496867|title=WWE WrestleMania 36 Will Move Forward For Now Amid Coronavirus Concerns|date=March 12, 2020|last=Konuwa|first=Alfred|work=[[Forbes]]|accessdate=March 12, 2020}}</ref> That same day, WWE announced that future episodes of their television programs (beginning with the March 11 episode of ''NXT'') will be filmed at the WWE Performance Center without an audience until further notice.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://bleacherreport.com/articles/2880809-report-wwe-moves-raw-on-316-day-featuring-stone-cold-to-performance-center|title=Report: WWE Moves Raw on '3:16 Day,' Featuring Stone Cold, to Performance Center|last=Blanchette|first=Rob|date=March 13, 2020|accessdate=March 13, 2020|work=[[Bleacher Report]]}}</ref> Meanwhile, AEW announced that it would relocate future episodes of ''Dynamite'' to [[Daily's Place]] in [[Jacksonville, Florida|Jacksonville]], with only essential personnel being allowed to attend.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cbr.com/aew-dynamite-coronavirus-venue-changes/|title=AEW Announces Venue Changes, Including Blood & Guts Show, Due to COVID-19|date=2020-03-13|website=CBR|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-15}}</ref>\n\nThe first episode of ''NXT'' after the announcement was emanated from the WWE headquarters in [[Stamford, Connecticut]], where hosts [[Triple H]] and [[Tom Phillips (wrestling)|Tom Phillips]] previewed several matches that are set to take place at WrestleMania 36 (one of which was set to involve [[Johnny Gargano]] and [[Tommaso Ciampa]]) and re-aired highlights from matches that were held over the previous few weeks.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ringsidenews.com/2020/03/18/wwe-nxt-results-march-18th-2020/| title=WWE NXT RESULTS \u2013 MARCH 18TH, 2020|last=Dunnells|first=Adam|work=[[Ringside News]]|date=March 18, 2020|accessdate=March 18, 2020}}</ref> Cody opened the corresponding episode of ''Dynamite'' with a short speech explaining the situation; in the main event, The Inner Circle defeated The Elite in a six-man tag team match, after which [[Matt Hardy]] debuted as Nick Jackson's replacement after he was attacked last week.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://bleacherreport.com/articles/2881811-aew-dynamite-results-winners-grades-reaction-and-highlights-from-march-18#slide1|work=[[Bleacher Report]]|date=March 18, 2020|accessdate=March 18, 2020|title=AEW Dynamite Results: Winners, Grades, Reaction and Highlights from March 18|last=Mueller|first=Chris}}</ref>\n\n==Comparison of viewers between ''NXT'' and ''Dynamite''==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable mw-collapsible mw-collapsed\" style=\"font-size: 85%\"\n! Date !! ''NXT''  !! ''Dynamite''\n|- style=\"background:#ddc34f;\"\n| 2019-10-02<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.showbuzzdaily.com/articles/showbuzzdailys-top-150-wednesday-cable-originals-network-finals-